{"id":1198902451,"created_at":"2022-04-10T06:27:35Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T15:23:58Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove Swing dependency of base source folder","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/3784","body":"The big problem of ADempiere is the bad use of dependencies.\r\nThe **base** source folder should have only the **core** without any **UI** related like **Swing** or **ZK**.\r\n\r\n## What is the problem?\r\nThe base source folder has many references to Swing UI like _JPanel_, _JButton_, and others that cause a problem if we want to get a clean **core**.\r\n\r\n## What is the initial solution?\r\n- Move the swing dependence from _base_ and change from base to _client_.\r\n- Create interfaces or contracts to manage mandatory dependencies like in the **View** inside **ReportEngine**\r\n- Add _Util_ class to provide generic methods used on **Swing** or **ZK**\r\n\r\nNote: _org.compiere.Adempiere_ was moved to _org.adempiere.Adempiere_ and now is running from _client_ source folder"}

{"id":1196838344,"created_at":"2022-04-08T05:15:04Z","updated_at":"2022-04-10T06:27:57Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove Swing dependency of base source folder","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/3781","body":"The big problem of ADempiere is the bad use of dependency.\r\nThe **base** source folder should have only the **core** without any **UI** related like **Swing** or **ZK**.\r\n\r\n## What is the problem?\r\nThe base source folder have many references to Swing UI like JPanel, JButton and others that make a problem if you want make a cleaned **core**\r\n\r\n## What is the initial solution?\r\n- Just move the swing dependence from base and change from base to client.\r\n- Creeate interfaces or contracts to manage mandatory dependences like is the **View** inside **ReportEngine**\r\n- Add Util class for provide generic methods used on **Swing** or **ZK**\r\n\r\nNote: org.compiere.Adempiere was moved to org.adempiere.Adempiere and now is running from client source folder"}

{"id":1198902451,"created_at":"2022-04-10T06:27:35Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T15:23:58Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove Swing dependency of base source folder","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/3784","body":"The big problem of ADempiere is the bad use of dependencies.\r\nThe **base** source folder should have only the **core** without any **UI** related like **Swing** or **ZK**.\r\n\r\n## What is the problem?\r\nThe base source folder has many references to Swing UI like _JPanel_, _JButton_, and others that cause a problem if we want to get a clean **core**.\r\n\r\n## What is the initial solution?\r\n- Move the swing dependence from _base_ and change from base to _client_.\r\n- Create interfaces or contracts to manage mandatory dependencies like in the **View** inside **ReportEngine**\r\n- Add _Util_ class to provide generic methods used on **Swing** or **ZK**\r\n\r\nNote: _org.compiere.Adempiere_ was moved to _org.adempiere.Adempiere_ and now is running from _client_ source folder"}

{"id":1196838344,"created_at":"2022-04-08T05:15:04Z","updated_at":"2022-04-10T06:27:57Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove Swing dependency of base source folder","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/3781","body":"The big problem of ADempiere is the bad use of dependency.\r\nThe **base** source folder should have only the **core** without any **UI** related like **Swing** or **ZK**.\r\n\r\n## What is the problem?\r\nThe base source folder have many references to Swing UI like JPanel, JButton and others that make a problem if you want make a cleaned **core**\r\n\r\n## What is the initial solution?\r\n- Just move the swing dependence from base and change from base to client.\r\n- Creeate interfaces or contracts to manage mandatory dependences like is the **View** inside **ReportEngine**\r\n- Add Util class for provide generic methods used on **Swing** or **ZK**\r\n\r\nNote: org.compiere.Adempiere was moved to org.adempiere.Adempiere and now is running from client source folder"}

{"id":1213825470,"created_at":"2022-04-25T00:59:45Z","updated_at":"2022-04-25T01:58:06Z","state":"closed","title":"Add frame configuration","html_url":"https://github.com/Allan-Jacobs/Swing-MVC/pull/11","body":"Swing-MVC has had a problem: there was no direct access to the internal JFrame. This meant you could not resize the gui, or have a diffent close operation. This PR adds a FrameConfiguration class, and a new method in App that allows for configuration to be done before the application loads. This enables the above uscases, among others. This PR is fully backwards compatiable, and should not require changes to dependant source code."}

{"id":1228123353,"created_at":"2022-05-06T17:36:41Z","updated_at":"2022-05-12T15:40:24Z","state":"closed","title":"[JENKINS-51820] Removing Java Web Start support","html_url":"https://github.com/jenkinsci/remoting/pull/532","body":"Preparation for dropping Java 8 support, since we did not support JWS on newer Java versions anyway.\r\n\r\n* GUI mode (Swing window) removed. This was normally only used in `javaws` launch mode.\r\n* `-headless` argument made into a no-op.\r\n* JAR signature removed, since this was only useful for convincing JWS that it was OK to run the JAR.\r\n  * (This also means that we no longer _need_ to use trusted.ci.jenkins.io to release; anyone with push access according to RPU could run MRP, or we could set up CD as we do for some other core components such as Stapler.)\r\n* Removing `SecurityManager` call which printed warnings on Java 17 (superseding #531 and thus also #481 & #507) since this was only used to undo what JWS did.\r\n\r\nShould only be merged & released if https://github.com/jenkinsci/jenkins/pull/6543 is also approved, as otherwise the GUI would offer an option which no longer works."}

{"id":1198671614,"created_at":"2022-04-09T15:14:37Z","updated_at":"2022-04-10T19:40:32Z","state":"closed","title":"Adds swing ui which monitors scijava's tasks","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/pull/67","body":"Adds a circular progress bar component to the status bar which  displays the overall progress of all registered tasks created via the scijava task service. When the user clicks on the circular progress bar, a frame containing a table summarizing each task progression is displayed.\r\n\r\nEach task is rendered in the table with a custom renderer, displaying a label with the name of the task and its status, a linear progress bar, and, if enabled, a label with an estimation of the remaining time until task completion. The estimation assumes a constant completion speed since the start of the task registration. Additionally, the second column of the table displays a clickable stop icon and which can be used to cancel the task.\r\n\r\n\r\nBefore cancellation, a user confirmation dialog can be enabled or disabled.\r\n\r\nNote: the scijava-common version is overriden in order to use the PR https://github.com/scijava/scijava-common/pull/432"}

This test was approved in the closed repo and has been converted to an open repo test.\r\n\r\nThis test checks if the coordinates are still correct after changing focuses between different JInternalFrames. The test is now automated instead of manual like the previous, closed version. This needs to be a headful test to allow robot to click on the different frames and to check coordinates.\r\n\r\nThe issue was that in MacOS, the button wouldn't appear at a normal size. To fix this, the bounds have been increased to allow the button to be fully visible with the designated frame sizes on all L&Fs.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8254759](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8254759): [TEST_BUG] [macosx] javax/swing/JInternalFrame/4202966/IntFrameCoord.html fails\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Phil Race](https://openjdk.java.net/census#prr) (@prrace - **Reviewer**)\n * [Alexander Zuev](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kizune) (@azuev-java - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8444/head:pull/8444` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8444`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8444` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8444/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8444`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8444`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8444.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8444.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}
{"id":1235584108,"created_at":"2022-05-13T19:01:01Z","updated_at":"2022-05-23T08:16:32Z","state":"closed","title":"Allow to use HeapProgress in head-less environment","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/visualvm/issues/406","body":"Currently `org.graalvm.visualvm.lib.jfluid.heap` module can be used as standalone library in head-less environment just fine. The only code, which uses `java.swing`, is used by progress. So if one wants to use `HeapProgress`, this must be done from UI - this way it is used by VisualVM. It would be useful to allow progress usage in head-less environment (command-line utilities, web server application)."}
{"id":1194389565,"created_at":"2022-04-06T10:11:33Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T07:31:16Z","state":"closed","title":"8282716: [macos] Enable javax/swing/JScrollPane/TestMouseWheelScroll.java on macos","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8123","body":"The test was failing on macos and was excluded in macos because the viewposition was not changed after mouse wheel scroll. Seems like mouse wheel scroll direction is opposite in macos compared to windows etc so if we try to down-wheel scroll in macos when view position is at center of viewport (say element 3 is selected out of visible 7 elements), it cannot change viewposition as it cannot \"scroll up\" (since we are already at topmost viewport) whereas in windows, when we do down-wheel scroll in mouse wheel, it \"scroll down\" the viewport so viewposition is changed.\r\n\r\nFix is to use opposite scrolling motion in macos to check mouse wheel scroll is happening, which is what the testcase is meant for. CI testing of this test on all platform is ok.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8282716](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8282716): [macos] Enable javax/swing/JScrollPane/TestMouseWheelScroll.java on macos\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Sergey Bylokhov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#serb) (@mrserb - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8123/head:pull/8123` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8123`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8123` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8123/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8123`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8123`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8123.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8123.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1165473210,"created_at":"2022-03-10T16:49:45Z","updated_at":"2022-03-16T17:53:18Z","state":"closed","title":"Fix Structure (Swing)","html_url":"https://github.com/bartosiewicz-b/Secure-Data/issues/4","body":"No content"}
{"id":1141069010,"created_at":"2022-02-17T09:18:59Z","updated_at":"2022-05-03T08:31:51Z","state":"closed","title":"SPARK-2257: Make execution on Event Dispatch Thread more explicit","html_url":"https://github.com/igniterealtime/Spark/pull/681","body":"Swing event handling code runs on a special thread known as the event dispatch thread. Most code that invokes Swing methods also runs on this thread. This is necessary because most Swing object methods are not \"thread safe\": invoking them from multiple threads risks thread interference or memory consistency errors. Some Swing component methods are labelled \"thread safe\" in the API specification; these can be safely invoked from any thread. All other Swing component methods must be invoked from the event dispatch thread. Programs that ignore this rule may function correctly most of the time, but are subject to unpredictable errors that are difficult to reproduce.\r\n\r\nIt's useful to think of the code running on the event dispatch thread as a series of short tasks. Most tasks are invocations of event-handling methods, such as ActionListener.actionPerformed. Other tasks can be scheduled by application code, using invokeLater or invokeAndWait. Tasks on the event dispatch thread must finish quickly; if they don't, unhandled events back up and the user interface becomes unresponsive.\r\n\r\nSpark should make clear what code is, and what code is not supposed to be executed on the Event Dispatch thread. This will help reduce instances where the UI seems frozen for prolonged periods of time, or otherwise behaves in an unexpected manner.\r\n\r\nThis commit adds comments to various methods (particularly around the login sequence) that define if the method is to be executed on the Event Dispatch Thread. Also, when ran in debug mode, code-checks will fail-fast, if such methods are executed differently. This will help spot problems."}
{"id":1190657251,"created_at":"2022-04-02T15:03:05Z","updated_at":"2022-04-22T12:28:40Z","state":"closed","title":"JTable: Fix absence of horizontal scrollbar and add popup menu actions","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/pull/63","body":"This ensures horizontal scrollbar is displayed when contents of table too small to fit in view port.\r\nIn addition, it implements a contextual menu hosting some basic actions:\r\n- Copy and Select All command (from the JTable action map)\r\n- Delete selected rows command\r\n- Resize command that enlarges column widths to largest cell in the column\r\n\r\nFixes https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/issues/62"}

{"id":1203409364,"created_at":"2022-04-13T14:47:50Z","updated_at":"2022-04-23T15:15:15Z","state":"closed","title":"BooleanRenderer provided by JTable doesnt respect striped background if using Table.alternateRowColor","html_url":"https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/issues/515","body":"The default String renderer provided by JTable works with Table.alternateRowColor but the Boolean Renderer does not. Not sure if would consider this a bug in JTable or something Flatlaf could resolve in JTableUI, but my solution was to make a copy of JTable.BooleanRenderer to  create new renderer with extra code in getTableCellRendererComponent()\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport javax.swing.*;\r\nimport javax.swing.border.Border;\r\nimport javax.swing.border.EmptyBorder;\r\nimport javax.swing.plaf.UIResource;\r\nimport javax.swing.table.TableCellRenderer;\r\nimport java.awt.*;\r\n\r\npublic class StripedBooleanRenderer extends JCheckBox implements TableCellRenderer, UIResource\r\n{\r\n    private static final Border noFocusBorder = new EmptyBorder(1, 1, 1, 1);\r\n\r\n    public StripedBooleanRenderer() {\r\n        super();\r\n        setHorizontalAlignment(JLabel.CENTER);\r\n        setBorderPainted(true);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public Component getTableCellRendererComponent(JTable table,\r\n                                                   Object value,\r\n                                                   boolean isSelected,\r\n                                                   boolean hasFocus,\r\n                                                   int row,\r\n                                                   int column)\r\n    {\r\n        if (isSelected)\r\n        {\r\n            setForeground(table.getSelectionForeground());\r\n            super.setBackground(table.getSelectionBackground());\r\n        }\r\n        else\r\n        {\r\n            setForeground(table.getForeground());\r\n            if(row % 2 ==0)\r\n            {\r\n                setBackground(table.getBackground());\r\n            }\r\n            else\r\n            {\r\n                setBackground(UIManager.getColor(\"Table.alternateRowColor\"));\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        setSelected((value != null && ((Boolean)value).booleanValue()));\r\n\r\n        if (hasFocus)\r\n        {\r\n            setBorder(UIManager.getBorder(\"Table.focusCellHighlightBorder\"));\r\n        } else\r\n        {\r\n            setBorder(noFocusBorder);\r\n        }\r\n        return this;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\nand then in subclass of JTable have\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n    public TableCellRenderer getDefaultRenderer(Class<?> columnClass)\r\n    {\r\n        if(columnClass==Boolean.class)\r\n        {\r\n            return new StripedBooleanRenderer();\r\n        }\r\n        return super.getDefaultRenderer(columnClass);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n```"}

{"id":1205620727,"created_at":"2022-04-15T14:26:53Z","updated_at":"2022-04-21T20:09:44Z","state":"closed","title":"Fix long delay when using \"undo all\" with lots of moves.","html_url":"https://github.com/triplea-game/triplea/pull/10315","body":"## Change Summary & Additional Notes\r\nFix long delay when using \"undo all\" with lots of moves.\r\n\r\nThe delay was caused by slow execution of resource bar updates. This change makes it so we only update it once if we receive lots of updates at once, assuming the swing code runs after the updates (which seems to be the case in the case of undo all).\r\n\r\nAlso makes the code more concise with some clean up.\r\n\r\n## Release Note\r\n<!--\r\nInclude a release note if there is a bug fix or a visible change for players.\r\nFor format & syntax help, see:\r\nhttps://github.com/triplea-game/triplea/blob/master/docs/development/reference/pr-release-notes.md\r\n-->\r\n\r\n<!--RELEASE_NOTE-->FIX|The undo all action has been sped up<!--END_RELEASE_NOTE-->\r\n"}

{"id":1165045389,"created_at":"2022-03-10T10:36:17Z","updated_at":"2022-03-10T11:40:18Z","state":"closed","title":"Don't depend on kotlinx-coroutines-swing","html_url":"https://github.com/JetBrains/androidx/pull/212","body":"Because it overrides Dispatchers.Main\r\n\r\nFixes https://github.com/JetBrains/compose-jb/issues/1943\r\n\r\nRelNote:\r\nCompose don't depend on `kotlinx-coroutines-swing` now. If you use `Dispatchers.Swing` or `Dispatchers.Main` in your code, add this dependency into `build.gradle.kts`:\r\n```\r\ndependencies {\r\n    implementation(\"org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-swing:$coroutinesVersion\")\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nAlso, usage of `Dispatchers.Swing` or `Dispatchers.Main` inside internals of Compose is implementation details, and can be changed in the future. If you need to avoid race conditions with Compose UI, you can obtain appropriate coroutine scope via `rememberCoroutineScope`:\r\n```\r\nimport androidx.compose.runtime.DisposableEffect\r\nimport androidx.compose.runtime.remember\r\nimport androidx.compose.runtime.rememberCoroutineScope\r\nimport androidx.compose.ui.ExperimentalComposeUiApi\r\nimport androidx.compose.ui.window.application\r\n\r\n@OptIn(ExperimentalComposeUiApi::class, androidx.compose.foundation.ExperimentalFoundationApi::class)\r\nfun main() = application {\r\n    val scope = rememberCoroutineScope()\r\n    val someApplicationObject = remember(scope) { SomeApplicationObject(scope) }\r\n    \r\n    DisposableEffect(Unit) {\r\n        SomeGlobalObject.init(scope)\r\n        onDispose {  }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```"}

{"id":1167633230,"created_at":"2022-03-13T16:49:00Z","updated_at":"2022-04-02T07:59:23Z","state":"closed","title":"[tado] Add support for fanLevel， verticalSwing， horizontalSwing， light API","html_url":"https://github.com/openhab/openhab-addons/pull/12470","body":"Fixes #12160\r\n\r\n## Background\r\nAs described in #12160 the Tado API has been extended for Air Conditioners to support more advanced features. Specifically these devices now support some additional JSON sub-elements as follows..\r\n1. A new `fanLevel` element providing extended fan speed possibilities compared to the earlier `fanspeed` element.\r\n2. Two new `verticalSwing`, `horizontalSwing` elements providing extended swing possibilities than the earlier `swing` element.\r\n3. A new `light` element for controlling the A/C unit panel light.\r\n\r\n@Artur-Fedjukevits made a first attempt to support these additional JSON elements; but instead of simply adding support for the new `fanLevel`, `verticalSwing`, & `horizontalSwing` elements, he mistakenly removed support for the prior `fanspeed` & `swing` elements. So his solution is not backward compatible with existing older devices.\r\n\r\nBy contrast, this PR is to add support for the new JSON elements, and still retain support for existing devices without breaking compatibility.\r\n\r\n## Notes:\r\n1. This PR introduces four new Channel types that correspond to the four new JSON elements.\r\n2. Depending on the brand of A/C unit and its operation mode, (i.e. depending on the capabilities), the choice of possible state option values adapts dynamically.\r\n3. This PR needs to be tested extensively by existing real users of Tado Air Conditioners.\r\n\r\nSigned-off-by: Andrew Fiddian-Green <software@whitebear.ch>"}

{"id":1172857942,"created_at":"2022-03-17T20:04:26Z","updated_at":"2022-04-25T22:21:45Z","state":"closed","title":"Native window decorations character encoding issue - Incorrect title shown on Windows taskbar","html_url":"https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/issues/502","body":"With native window decorations enabled, a window title containing Unicode characters is not displayed correctly in the Windows Taskbar, Taskbar tooltip, Task Manager etc.\r\n\r\nThe issue occurs if the title is updated **after** the window is visible. In the sample below, both frames will display the same title on the frame, but the second frame will display ?'s in the Windows Taskbar and elsewhere.\r\n\r\nThe issue does not occur with native window decorations disabled.\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport java.awt.event.WindowAdapter;\r\nimport java.awt.event.WindowEvent;\r\n\r\nimport javax.swing.JFrame;\r\nimport javax.swing.SwingUtilities;\r\nimport javax.swing.UIManager;\r\nimport javax.swing.UnsupportedLookAndFeelException;\r\nimport javax.swing.WindowConstants;\r\n\r\nimport com.formdev.flatlaf.FlatLaf;\r\nimport com.formdev.flatlaf.FlatLightLaf;\r\n\r\npublic class NativeWindowTitleIssue\r\n{\r\n\tpublic static void main(String[] args) {\r\n\t\ttry {\r\n\t\t\tUIManager.setLookAndFeel(new FlatLightLaf());\r\n\t\t\tFlatLaf.setUseNativeWindowDecorations(true);\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\tcatch (UnsupportedLookAndFeelException e) {\r\n\t\t\te.printStackTrace();\r\n\t\t}\r\n\r\n\t\tSwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> initGUI());\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tprivate static void initGUI() {\r\n\t\tString title = \"Ελληνικά Γράμματα\";\r\n\r\n\t\tcreateFrame(\"Good - \" + title, false);\r\n\t\tcreateFrame(\"Bad - \" + title, true);\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tprivate static void createFrame(String title, boolean updateTitle) {\r\n\t\tJFrame frame = new JFrame();\r\n\t\tframe.setSize(300, 200);\r\n\t\tframe.setDefaultCloseOperation(WindowConstants.DISPOSE_ON_CLOSE);\r\n\t\tframe.setLocationRelativeTo(null);\r\n\t\tframe.setTitle(title);\r\n\r\n\t\tif (updateTitle) {\r\n\t\t\tframe.addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {\r\n\t\t\t\t@Override\r\n\t\t\t\tpublic void windowOpened(WindowEvent e)\r\n\t\t\t\t{\r\n\t\t\t\t\tframe.setTitle(title);\r\n\t\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t\t});\r\n\t\t}\r\n\r\n\t\tframe.setVisible(true);\r\n\t}\r\n}\r\n```"}

The hope tree for this first change is:\r\n\r\n- Tools:\r\n  - Base: ADempiere micro-core:\r\n    - Install and external integrations:\r\n      - Install\r\n      - Migration\r\n      - Jasper Report\r\n      - Web Services\r\n      - Migrate\r\n    - Business Logic:\r\n      - Request\r\n      - Project\r\n      - Cash Flow\r\n      - Human Resource\r\n      - Manufacturing\r\n      - Warehouse Management System\r\n      - Fixed Assets\r\n      - POS\r\n      - Freight Management\r\n      - Production Light\r\n      - Fleet Management\r\n      - CRM\r\n      - Finance and Investing Management\r\n      - Loan Management\r\n      - Store\r\n    - Default Supported UI's:\r\n      - Client: Swing UI\r\n      - ZK: ZK UI\r\n    - Server Tasks and features:\r\n      - LDap\r\n      - Scheduler\r\n      - Alert Processor\r\n\r\nThe final scope is keep a core very little, simple, easy of port to\r\nother pattern desing and manage a better dependence and easy future\r\nrefactory"}

{"id":1150831267,"created_at":"2022-02-25T20:16:06Z","updated_at":"2022-05-13T17:53:29Z","state":"closed","title":"#3742 [Feature Request] Add support the Import Order in Parallel and …","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/3743","body":"The new approach:\r\n\r\n- Now the transactions shorter and this cause releasing database locks\r\n\r\n- Import logic was changed, using a parallel import, based on the document number and other fields that group the records to be imported.\r\n\r\n- Now are searches all import order records sorted by Organization Id, Business Partner, Business Partner Location, Bill To, Document Type, and Document No.\r\n\r\n- Mark all the records as in processing, so that if the import is executed by another user, it does not cause strange behavior when trying to import the same records by a user simultaneously.\r\n\r\n- All records are grouping by fields (Organization Id, Business Partner, Business Partner Location, Bill To, Document Type, and Document No), a Order is create and import the order lines in a execution in to parallel with short transactions.\r\n\r\n- Finally, at the end of creating the orders, apply the document action to the orders that were created without any errors in their lines.\r\n\r\n- In the event that a line to be imported has an error, it is not imported but the exception is registered to document the problem, and this order is marked so that no document action is executed, leaving the order in a draft state.\r\n\r\nFixed #3742\r\nRelation with #3712 \r\n"}

{"id":1233247554,"created_at":"2022-05-11T22:35:32Z","updated_at":"2022-05-18T16:29:39Z","state":"closed","title":"8286422: Add OIDs for RC2 and Blowfish","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8668","body":"Add missing OIDs for 2 secret key algorithms. These will be used when storing secret keys in a PKCS12 keystore. Like DES and DESede, the OIDs were originally defined for CBC mode cipher algorithms, they are reused here for key algorithms.\r\n\r\nOpenSSL uses the same OIDs for cipher algorithms.\r\n```\r\n1 3 6 1 4 1 3029 1 2\t: BF-CBC\t\t: bf-cbc\r\nrsadsi 3 2\t\t: RC2-CBC\t\t: rc2-cbc\r\n```\r\n\r\nSimilar to DES, RC2 is only added as an alias so it needs to be specially treated when getting a secret key entry from a PKCS12 keystore.\r\n\r\nNo attempt is made to define these OIDs as aliases to existing cipher algorithms.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed (1 review required, with at least 1 reviewer)\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8286422](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8286422): Add OIDs for RC2 and Blowfish\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Hai-May Chao](https://openjdk.java.net/census#hchao) (@haimaychao - Committer)\n * [Anthony Scarpino](https://openjdk.java.net/census#ascarpino) (@ascarpino - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8668/head:pull/8668` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8668`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8668` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8668/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8668`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8668`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8668.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8668.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1233648390,"created_at":"2022-05-12T08:43:56Z","updated_at":"2022-05-13T01:56:09Z","state":"closed","title":"8286623: Bundle zlib by default with JDK on macos aarch64","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8675","body":"Can I please get a review of this change to the build system which now makes bundled zlib as the default for macos aarch64 systems? \r\n\r\nWe have been running into various intermittent failures on macos aarch64 systems for several months now. After investigation we have been able to ascertain that the root cause of the issue lies within the zlib that's shipped on macos aarch64 systems. The complete details about that issue is available at https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8282954. \r\nWe have filed a bug with Apple for their inputs on what we can do to fix it in that shipped library. Given the nature of that issue, we don't have a timeline on when/if the solution for that will be available. Until that time, at least, the proposal is to use bundled zlib (which doesn't reproduce those failures) by default on macos aarch64.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed (1 review required, with at least 1 reviewer)\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8286623](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8286623): Bundle zlib by default with JDK on macos aarch64\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Lance Andersen](https://openjdk.java.net/census#lancea) (@LanceAndersen - **Reviewer**)\n * [Magnus Ihse Bursie](https://openjdk.java.net/census#ihse) (@magicus - **Reviewer**)\n * [Erik Joelsson](https://openjdk.java.net/census#erikj) (@erikj79 - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8675/head:pull/8675` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8675`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8675` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8675/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8675`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8675`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8675.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8675.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1232234598,"created_at":"2022-05-11T08:49:46Z","updated_at":"2022-05-12T13:10:54Z","state":"closed","title":"8286573: Remove the unnecessary method Attr#attribTopLevel and its usage","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8648","body":"Hi all,\r\n\r\nThe original patch [1] added the method `Attr#attribTopLevel` to validate the annotations of the package. Then the annotation validation was moved to the annotation pipeline [2] and the TopLevel tree node was refactored (added JCPackageDecl) [3]. So now the `Attr#attribTopLevel` is replaced by method `attribPackage` and actually is not used by any code. It is good to remove it.\r\n\r\nAnd there are only 3 places (shown below) that add the `Env` instance to the `Todo` list which the `Attr` uses as input. They add the `Env` of module, package, class seperately to the todo list . So the `Attr` doesn't need to handle the situation about TopLevel JCCompilationUnit.\r\n\r\n1. Enter::visitTopLevel  `todo.append(packageEnv)`\r\n2. Enter::visitModuleDef `todo.append(moduleEnv)`\r\n3. {"id":1127814622,"created_at":"2022-02-08T22:14:23Z","updated_at":"2022-04-28T20:34:20Z","state":"closed","title":"Module with javafx plugin is always considered out-of-date in a fresh gradle daemon","html_url":"https://github.com/openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin/issues/123","body":"A Gradle module has the following configuration:\r\n```groovy\r\nplugins {\r\n\tid 'org.openjfx.javafxplugin' version '0.0.9'\r\n}\r\n\r\njavafx {\r\n\tconfiguration = 'api'\r\n\tversion = '17'\r\n\tmodules = ['javafx.base', 'javafx.controls', 'javafx.fxml', 'javafx.graphics', 'javafx.media', 'javafx.swing', 'javafx.web']\r\n}\r\n```\r\nThe module is reported as UP-TO-DATE when running assemble twice:\r\n```bash\r\ngradle assemble\r\ngradle assemble\r\n```\r\n\r\nI would now expect the module to be UP-TO-DATE when stopping the Gradle Daemon between the two assemble runs:\r\n```bash\r\ngradle assemble\r\ngradle --stopp\r\ngradle assemble\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever this is not  the case. Strangely when ran with the `--info` switch, Gradle reports that the input property `Classpath` was changed and the module therefore needs to be rebuilt.\r\n```\r\nTask ':common-fx:compileJava' is not up-to-date because:\r\n  Input property 'classpath' file /home/ursl/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.openjfx/javafx-swing/17/8dee489b0faecf27568bfe64efdc7aa01410defa/javafx-swing-17-linux.jar has been removed.\r\n  Input property 'classpath' file /home/ursl/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.openjfx/javafx-web/17/bbd71beaf561b72f0d3eb6268d3114573b7799c3/javafx-web-17-linux.jar has been added.\r\n  Input property 'classpath' file /home/ursl/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.openjfx/javafx-web/17/bbd71beaf561b72f0d3eb6268d3114573b7799c3/javafx-web-17-linux.jar has been removed.\r\n```\r\nEven more strangely, these reported changes are not consistent. The \"changed\" dependencies vary every time the above commands are repeated."}

{"id":1231505708,"created_at":"2022-05-10T17:59:58Z","updated_at":"2022-05-12T15:18:45Z","state":"closed","title":"8286015 JFR: Remove jfr.save.generated.asm","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8637","body":"Could I have a review of a fix that removes the jfr.save.generated.asm property.\r\n\r\nIt was a developer property that could be set to write generated JFR .class files to disk. The mechanism doesn't work due to a bug, but nobody has noticed it for years. {"id":1146274889,"created_at":"2022-02-21T22:26:03Z","updated_at":"2022-04-18T19:54:12Z","state":"closed","title":"#550 decompress gzip files bigger than 10000 bytes","html_url":"https://github.com/otros-systems/otroslogviewer/pull/594","body":"The old implementation try to unzip the first 10,000 bytes of a gzip file. Read first 2 bytes to check if it is a gzip file\r\n2. Read direct from imputstream to decompress first 10,000 bytes\r\n3. {"id":1196027099,"created_at":"2022-04-07T13:10:57Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T13:17:57Z","state":"closed","title":"8284125: AArch64: Remove partial masked operations for SVE","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8144","body":"Currently there are match rules named as xxx_masked_partial, which are\r\nexpected to work on masked vector operations when the vector size is not\r\nthe full size of hardware vector reg width, i.e. partial vector. Those\r\nrules will make sure the given masked (predicate) high bits are cleared\r\nwith vector width. Actually, for those masked rules with predicate\r\ninput, if we can guarantee the input predicate high bits are already\r\ncleared with vector width, we don't need to re-do the clear work before\r\nuse. Currently, there are only 4 nodes on AArch64 backend which\r\ninitializes (defines) predicate registers:\r\n\r\n  1.MaskAllNode\r\n  2.VectorLoadMaskNode\r\n  3.VectorMaskGen\r\n  4.VectorMaskCmp\r\n\r\nWe can ensure that the predicate register will be well initialized with\r\nproper vector size, so that most of the masked partial rules with a mask\r\ninput could be removed.\r\n\r\n[TEST]\r\nvector api jtreg tests passed on my SVE testing system.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284125](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284125): AArch64: Remove partial masked operations for SVE\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Ningsheng Jian](https://openjdk.java.net/census#njian) (@nsjian - Committer)\n * [Nick Gasson](https://openjdk.java.net/census#ngasson) (@nick-arm - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8144/head:pull/8144` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8144`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8144` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8144/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8144`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8144`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8144.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8144.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1150948595,"created_at":"2022-02-25T22:58:00Z","updated_at":"2022-04-13T15:59:10Z","state":"closed","title":"Add CalculationReport tools","html_url":"https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/pull/3469","body":"I noticed that I need to write a conversion report for AlphaStrike conversion. Looking at the BV or cost reports, these are really done per pedes with mountains of stringbuilder.append(ROW_START). I wanted a tool for this, so this is the result and I'd rather add it now than keep it buried in the AS conversion branch.\r\n\r\nThis consists of an interface \"CalculationReport\" that writes up ths standard interaction with any of the report classes, such as addLine(String, String, String), addHeader() and so on.\r\nThe interface is implemented by four classes. These are:\r\n- HTMLCalculationReport: This creates a report much like it's done now, only without having to use any HTML manually\r\n- SwingCalculationReport: This creates a report using Swing Labels, ready to deploy in a panel or wherever; this is a bit superior to HTML as it knows how wide it wants to be and it is easier to format if any formatting is required. (see screen below)\r\n- TextCalculationReport: This is a pure text report, formatted for display in a monospace font. Good for export (see screen below)\r\n- In addition, there is FlexibleCalculationReport, which internally builds all three of the above and has any of them ready, for example for export to clipboard.\r\n\r\nAdding a line to any of the four is the same regardless of which Report type is used (and they can be typed as CalculationReport instead of their class): addLine(\"Damage:\", \"2+4+6\", \" = 12\"); Adding any of them to a dialog is simple as they all have a toJComponent() method.\r\n\r\nFor the examples below, I changed the bv calculation of Mech to the new way (which cuts around 700 lines of code and, I believe, a few bugs along the way). This is not part of the PR as I would need to convert all unit types and thats a lot. Something for later.\r\nThe code using it starts with:\r\nbvReport.addHeader(\"Battle Value Calculations For \" + getChassis() + \" \" + getModel());\r\nbvReport.addSubHeader(\"Defensive Battle Rating Calculation:\");\r\n\r\nTo switch between these two screenshots I changed only one line:\r\nCalculationReport bvReport = new TextCalculationReport(); <-> CalculationReport bvReport = new SwingCalculationReport();\r\n(and set the font to monospaced for the text)\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17069663/155806575-a971df23-74f7-4977-b1ff-67a1ec6d400c.png)\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17069663/155808061-baa6ba5d-fa7a-4a09-92c0-96865782fcbd.png)\r\n\r\n(There is a bug in the screenshots that has been corrected in the code)\r\n"}

k < K; k++) {\r\n\t\t\tst = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine(), \" \");\r\n\t\t\tint x1 = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());\r\n\t\t\tint y1 = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());\r\n\t\t\tint x2 = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());\r\n\t\t\tint y2 = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\tfor(int i = y1; i < y2; i++) {\r\n\t\t\t\tfor(int j = x1; j < x2; j++) {\r\n\t\t\t\t\tpaper[i][j] = true;\r\n\t\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\tArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();\r\n\t\tfor(int i = 0; i < M; i++) {\r\n\t\t\tfor(int j = 0; j < N; j++) {\r\n\t\t\t\tif(!paper[i][j]) {\r\n\t\t\t\t\tarea = 0;\r\n\t\t\t\t\tdfs(i, j);\r\n\t\t\t\t\tcnt++;\r\n\t\t\t\t\tlist.add(area);\r\n\t\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\tCollections.sort(list);\r\n\t\tsb.append(cnt).append(\"\\n\");\r\n\t\tfor(int n : list) {\r\n\t\t\tsb.append(n).append(\" \");\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\tSystem.out.println(sb);\r\n\t\tbr.close();\r\n\t}\r\n\t\r\n\tstatic void dfs(int x, int y) {\r\n\t\tpaper[x][y] = true;\r\n\t\tarea++;\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\tfor(int d = 0; d < 4; d++) {\r\n\t\t\tint nx = x + dir[d][0];\r\n\t\t\tint ny = y + dir[d][1];\r\n\t\t\tif(0 <= nx && nx < M && 0 <= ny && ny < N && !paper[nx][ny]) {\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\tdfs(nx, ny);\r\n\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t}\r\n}\r\n\r\n```\r\n"}

{"id":1181282049,"created_at":"2022-03-25T21:24:42Z","updated_at":"2022-04-05T20:39:11Z","state":"closed","title":"Bring Task Tree UI closer to native IntelliJ Build window","html_url":"https://github.com/bazelbuild/intellij/pull/3386","body":"Bring Task Tree UI closer to native IntelliJ Build window\n\nRefactors TasksTreeView tree to use the StructureTreeModel/AsyncTreeModel backed by Tasks as PresentationNodeDescriptors.\n\nIt essentially decouples the TasksTreeModel from the TreeModel powering the Swing Tree, requiring a small change to calculations of TreePaths from a given Task and how we were handling selection of newly added tasks. Previously, the TasksTreeModel selected a new task upon adding it, but with the AsyncTreeModel, this would result in an attempt to select a task before it had actually been added to the tree view. Since we don't want to automatically select all new tasks anyway, the tree handles selection (still delegating to the TasksTreeModel) when tasks are added.\n\nModifies UI to\n- Display duration strings on the right of the tree window while a task is running\n- Display finishing time only on the top level task\n- Only select newly added tasks when they are top-level tasks\n- Auto-expand the first level of tasks\n"}

{"id":1185463622,"created_at":"2022-03-29T21:59:08Z","updated_at":"2022-04-07T20:22:08Z","state":"closed","title":"Task interface and DefaultTask modifications - backward compatible","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-common/pull/432","body":"With this PR task events are published automatically when an asynchronous task (task.run(runnable)))\r\nis started and finished. Additionally, task can be run in a synchronous manner and can trigger task events\r\nwith additional methods added to the Task interface.\r\n\r\nThis commit brings additional methods to the Task interface (empty default implementations provided):\r\n* start and finish method: a job can notify when it is starting and ending in a synchronous manner\r\n* setCancelCallback(runnable) method: Can be used to add a callback when a task is canceled\r\n\r\nThe DefaultTask implementation is modified:\r\n* TaskEvent are published when start() and finish() are called (synchronous task)\r\n* TaskEvent are published just before the runnable is started and after it is  finished\r\n* A try finally statement is used in the async case to ensure a taskevent is sent even in the case of job execution failure\r\n* And event is called when cancel is called, and:\r\n  * Async job : future.cancel(true) is called, + the custom cancel callback is called, if set\r\n  * Sync job : the custom cancel callback is called, if set\r\n\r\n* adds a test to check whether many parallel tasks send an event when they are starting and when they are done\r\n* documentation\r\n\r\nSee also : forum post describing the functionality: https://forum.image.sc/t/demo-and-proposal-new-progress-bars-for-fiji/64956\r\n\r\nDraft PR for full functionality will be done in scijava-ui-swing, imagej-legacy and batch-processor"}

{"id":963476485,"created_at":"2021-08-08T17:14:26Z","updated_at":"2022-04-30T02:34:05Z","state":"closed","title":"WIP - SPI for LnMenu item extension","html_url":"https://github.com/JMRI/JMRI/pull/10028","body":"This P/R provides an mechanism to allow \"extension\" code in a separate JAR file to integrate its own `...loconet.swing.LnPanel`-based functionality into the JMRI LocoNet connection's menu.\r\n\r\nThis mechanism uses JAVA SPI methodologies, both in JMRI and in the 3rd-party \"extension\", to provide the link between JMRI and the extension.\r\n\r\nThe key modifications to `...loconet.swing.LocoNetMenu.java` are found in lines 112 to 141.  The SPI \"interface\" is defined in `...loconet.swing.spi.LnMenuItemExtension.java`.  The SPI \"service\" is implemented in `...loconet.swing.LnMenuItemExtensionService.java`.  \r\n\r\n`...loconet.swing.LnMenuItem.java` provides the data structure which conveys the menu item text and the class which the menu item will invoke.  It also includes a LocoNet-specific boolean that is used to determine whether the menu item applies for the connection type.  A connection which only allows decoder programming on the service track does not need a tool to configure a LocoNet-connected device; this boolean value allows selective filtering of menu items based on need to access to a physical LocoNet's devices.\r\n\r\nSee [https://github.com/devel-bobm/sampleLnMenuExtension](url) for example code which implements a simple extension (i.e. a SPI \"service provider) which provides a LnPanel containing a pushbutton which sends LocoNet \"power on\" and \"power off\" messages, and which shows the most-recently-received LocoNet message, in hexadecimal digit pairs.  This gives a simple example of how such a 3rd-party extension may make use of existing JMRI code features to interact with the LocoNet connection, without including 3rd-party code within the JMRI code-base.\r\n\r\nHow to make use of this P/R and the sample extension\r\n\r\n1) Apply the P/R code to JMRI.  Create a `jmri.jar` file containing those changes.  If desired, create a new \"installer\" and install the modified JMRI version.\r\n2) Create the `sampleLnMenuItemExtension.jar` file using whatever mechanisms you prefer.  Note that it is necessary to _compile_ the java source using the libraries listed below.  I simply configure the project to reference the `jmri.jar` file in the `dist` directory of my local JMRI repository library, and to reference the library files from the local JMRI repository `lib` directory.\r\n- `jmri.jar`\r\n- `org-openide-util-lookup-RELEASE113.jar`\r\n- `jsr305.jar`\r\n\r\n3) Modify your environment to include \"sampleLnMenuExtension.jar\" in JMRI's `CLASSPATH`.  I generally work in an IDE via ant, so I copy the .jar to JMRI's `lib` directory, and modify build.xml to include the .jar file in the `runtime.class.path` .\r\n4) Run JMRI, configure a LocoNet connection (if not already available), and select the LocoNet connection's menu.  The last element in the menu should be \"Extension Menu Item\".\r\n\r\nI leave it up to the individual developer to figure out how to configure the developement environment to compile using this set of libraries, and to figure out how to include the extension's jar file in the `CLASSPATH` in the run-time environment.\r\n"}

{"id":1195756754,"created_at":"2022-04-07T09:17:02Z","updated_at":"2022-05-26T06:33:48Z","state":"closed","title":"8257810: Only First page are printed in JTable.scrollRectToVisible","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8141","body":"Issue was when printing a JTable which sits inside a JScrollPane and the table is scrolled down to the end to about 1000th row, only the first page is printed. \r\nThis is because when the table is scrolled down to last page, the bounds.y becomes -ve \r\n[x=0,y=-15260,width=968,height=16000]\r\nso the check `if (!((table.getBounds()).intersects(clip)))` is satisfied only for 1st page where bounds just intersects the clip [x=0,y=0,width=968,height=1296]\r\nbut subsequent pages clip \r\n[[x=0,y=1296,width=968,height=1296], \r\n[x=0,y=2592,width=968,height=1296], \r\n[x=0,y=3888,width=968,height=1296] etc is not intesecting so they are not printed\r\n\r\nThis is a regression of JDK-8081491 which was **reworked** in JDK-8236907 where the bounds calculation and usage is made same as in BasicTableUI\r\nWe need to use the same resetted bounds for this intersection calculation too as was done for JDK-8236907\r\n\r\nTested against JDK-8081491, 8170349, JDK-8236907 testcases along with other regression tests and all are OK (link in JBS)\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! {"id":1192436767,"created_at":"2022-04-04T23:46:57Z","updated_at":"2022-04-14T19:57:06Z","state":"closed","title":"JDK-8283714: REDO - Unexpected TypeElement in ANALYZE TaskEvent","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8101","body":"This is a redo of a recent fix, which passed all tier1 tests but broke \"make docs\".\r\n\r\nThe reason for the crash was a combination of a number of factors, such that fixing any one (or more) would make the problem go away, making it hard(er) to determine the correct path forward.\r\n\r\n1. In a doc comment in JDK code, the author had mistakenly written a number of tags like `{@link byte}` instead of `{@code byte}` and `{@link byte[]}` instead of `{@code byte[]}`\r\n\r\n2. `DocTrees.getElement` returns the javac-internal symbol for primitive types (instead of `null`) and the base type for arrays. So for both `{@link byte}` and `{@link byte[]}` the `LinkFactory` was given a javac-internal symbol (instead of null).  Filed as JDK-8284315.\r\n\r\n3. Thinking the value was a declared type, and so in a named or unnamed package, the `LinkFactory` attempts to create a link based on the package of the value.    The package for the java-internal symbols for primitive type is a special `rootPackage` which has no equivalent in the Language Model world, and which has a `null` owner.\r\n\r\n4. The new code in `JavacElements.getModuleOf` assumes that (as is generally standard in javac) all symbols have a non-`null` owner, this giving an NPE when called with `rootPackage`.\r\n\r\nSo, there are various possible ways to fix this.\r\n\r\n1. put a broad null check for `sym.owner` in `JavacElements.getModuleOf`\r\n2. put a specific check for `rootPackage` in `JavacElements.getMOduleOf`\r\n3. fix `DocTrees.getElement` to not return javac-internal symbols\r\n4. change javadoc to workaround the issue with `DocTrees.getElement`\r\n5. fix the javadoc comments to not use bad forms, like `{@link byte}` etc.\r\n\r\n1 and 2 would both be atypical idioms in the code.\r\n\r\n3 is desirable, but may cause additional work/updates/etc. It would be a change to the behavior of a public API, and so compatibility concerns would need to be addressed, although arguably the change in behavior is a bug fix, not a spec change. (The current behavior is under-specified!)\r\n\r\nBy itself, 5 would just be ignoring the underlying problem.\r\n\r\nThat leaves 4, which is the solution adopted here. It localizes the change/check to javadoc internal code. It is an interim measure until we can fix 3. (JDK-8284315)\r\n\r\n* The javac part of the fix is essentially the same as before (a redundant import has been removed, this time.)  By itself the code was not wrong, when used as intended.\r\n\r\n* `DocTrees.getElement` is called from a single place in javadoc, in `CommentHelper` and so a check is made on the result such that `null` is returned when the result would otherwise not be a declared type.\r\n\r\n* A new (javadoc) test is added to verify the new behavior for `{@link byte}` etc. The prior behavior (even before the original fix) was to display the type in monospace font.  The new behavior is for javadoc to fall back on the recently-new mechanism to display a \"invalid tag\" block.\r\n\r\nWith these fixes, \"make docs\" works, and does not crash(!) Comparing the result of \"make docs\" before and after this fix, the only significant differences arise from the 5 bad `{@link ...}` tags in `MemorySegment.java`. These should (separately) be fixed.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issues\n * [JDK-8283714](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8283714): REDO - Unexpected TypeElement in ANALYZE TaskEvent\n * [JDK-8284030](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284030): Standard Doclet should not attempt to link to primitive types\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Vicente Romero](https://openjdk.java.net/census#vromero) (@vicente-romero-oracle - **Reviewer**) ⚠️ Review applies to bbec4f326a59a0731db0c97476b1f01b52096294\n * [Jan Lahoda](https://openjdk.java.net/census#jlahoda) (@lahodaj - **Reviewer**) ⚠️ Review applies to bbec4f326a59a0731db0c97476b1f01b52096294\n * [Pavel Rappo](https://openjdk.java.net/census#prappo) (@pavelrappo - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8101/head:pull/8101` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8101`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8101` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8101/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8101`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8101`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8101.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8101.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1197596332,"created_at":"2022-04-08T17:45:02Z","updated_at":"2022-04-11T16:20:20Z","state":"closed","title":"BV Calculations use CalculationReport","html_url":"https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/pull/3556","body":"The BV calculations again... revamped to use CalculationReports. This finishes up the refactors.\r\n\r\nWithin the calculations there is no logic change, just lots of \"bvText.append();\" replaced with somewhat less CalculationReport.addLines(). This also removes the need for the BVCalculation superclass.\r\n\r\nThis required some adaptation in Entity (again) for how to call the BV calculations. They can now be called with a CalculationReport parameter to obtain the report or without it in which case the report is written to a dummy and ditched. The bv reports are only called from the BVDisplayDialog (no explicit calls in MML/MHQ) so this is adapted accordingly. It has now two buttons that allow export of the report as text or HTML. I also made the dialog override its stored size and instead adapt to the content as I found I couldn't find a size for it that felt good, the reports are too different from each other in width and height."}

{"id":1119520855,"created_at":"2022-01-31T14:43:12Z","updated_at":"2022-05-04T07:52:29Z","state":"closed","title":"New toolbar with button","html_url":"https://github.com/JMMC-OpenDev/oimaging/pull/83","body":"Related Issue https://github.com/JMMC-OpenDev/oimaging/issues/69\r\nRelated OITOOLS PR https://github.com/JMMC-OpenDev/oitools/pull/48\r\n\r\nAdd four buttons to the action panel in result tab.\r\n- Run more iterations\r\n- Load as input\r\n- Load as input with last img\r\n- Set as init img\r\n\r\nThe major update is the new flow of data in the software. Now a result can be selected by the user and sent to fill the input form. Previously data from results never went outside results. This PR goes with the OITOOLS PR which implements the copy of OIFITSFILE, needed to use the data of a result without altering it.\r\n\r\nSecondary, three actions have been created for the new buttons. to load the result in input, the result oifitsfile is copied, then given to the existing function loadOIFitsFile from IRModel.\r\n\r\nThe new button provoke more duplicates in the image library than before, the issue alternative checksum https://github.com/JMMC-OpenDev/oimaging/issues/82 has been created to answer it.\r\n\r\nThe copy of oifitsfile from result to input form has a problem, because the results do not keep oifits data identical. Not only they add some OI TABLE but also they remove some OI TABLE. My local branch https://github.com/buthanoid/oimaging/tree/fix-oifits-data-missing-in-result-2 is a proposal to resolve this problem for the release. \r\n\r\nEach run adds a suffix to the filename, since we now use results as inputs, filename can grow large. a small fix has been added to prevent this filename from growing too much (which was buggy). A clean solution is left as a TODO."}

{"id":1191846438,"created_at":"2022-04-04T14:05:14Z","updated_at":"2022-05-04T07:49:14Z","state":"closed","title":"8284294: Create an automated regression test for RFE 4138746","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8093","body":"Create an automated regression test for [JDK-4138746](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-4138746)\r\n\r\nIssue:\r\nIn the following example (and similarly with other components) you cannot specify the correct character to underline:\r\n\r\nJLabel label = new JLabel (\"Save As...\");\r\nlabel.setDisplayedMnemonic ('A');\r\n\r\nThe 'A' in 'As' should be underlined (that's the intention at least), but the 'a' in 'Save' is what gets underlined.\r\n\r\nThe problem (aside from the lack of an API to specify exactly what should be underlined) is in the javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicGraphicUtils drawString method which underlines the first character (upper OR lowercase) that matches the mnemonic character.\r\n\r\nFix:\r\nA new property \"displayedMnemonicIndex\" is introduced\r\nin classes AbstractButton and JLabel. It tells which\r\ncharacter to underline. So for example to underline\r\nthe capital 'A' in 'Save As', one should call:\r\n    setMnemonic('A');\r\n    setDisplayedMnemonicIndex(5);\r\n\r\nTesting:\r\nTested in Mach5 10 times per platform and got all Pass.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284294](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284294): Create an automated regression test for RFE 4138746\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Sergey Bylokhov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#serb) (@mrserb - **Reviewer**) ⚠️ Review applies to 9c951603ecf299c06d80adcff8b7ff947df06d8d\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8093/head:pull/8093` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8093`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8093` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8093/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8093`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8093`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8093.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8093.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1124952478,"created_at":"2022-02-05T15:07:06Z","updated_at":"2022-02-23T09:24:11Z","state":"closed","title":"demo_chat - v1","html_url":"https://github.com/BorodinovYuriy/geekbrains_quarter_1/pull/11","body":"Знакомство с библиотекой swing (JFrame)"}
{"id":1197217706,"created_at":"2022-04-08T11:45:13Z","updated_at":"2022-05-19T09:54:14Z","state":"closed","title":"8284578: Relax InterpreterCodelet stub alignment","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8159","body":"`InterpreterCodelet` is aligned by `CodeEntryAlignment` (`CAE`) twice. First, the entire stub is aligned, which aligns its data section. Then, the code section in the stub is aligned. Since `CAE` is usually larger than the size of `InterpreterCodelet`, we are wasting quite a bit of space for each codelet. In the extreme cases, like PPC that defaults to `CAE=128`, we have 16 bytes of codelet data effectively taking 128 bytes!\r\n\r\nThis can be made better by relaxing the `InterpreterCodelet` stub alignment to `HeapWordSize`, while leaving its code section alignment the same.\r\n\r\nThis tangentially touches the only other user for `StubQueue`: `ICStub`. Unfortunately, we cannot do the same kind of relaxation there, because there is a reverse lookup function that needs to reach data section from the code section, which forces us to keep the same alignment for both.\r\n\r\nInterpreter sizes on Linux x86_64 release:\r\n\r\n```\r\n# Baseline, CEA=32 (default)\r\ncode size        =     94K bytes\r\navg codelet size =    356  bytes\r\n\r\n# Baseline, CEA=128 (PPC-like)\r\ncode size        =    133K bytes\r\navg codelet size =    501  bytes\r\n\r\n# Patched, CEA=32 (default)\r\ncode size        =     89K bytes\r\navg codelet size =    338  bytes\r\n\r\n# Patched, CEA=128 (PPC-like)\r\ncode size        =    100K bytes\r\navg codelet size =    380  bytes\r\n```\r\n\r\nPoint performance runs (SPECjvm2008:serial with `-Xint` on Linux x86_64 release):\r\n\r\n```\r\nBenchmark     Mode  Cnt   Score   Error  Units\r\n\r\n# Baseline, CEA=32\r\nSerial.test  thrpt    9  73.427 ± 0.152  ops/s\r\n\r\n# Baseline, CEA=128\r\nSerial.test  thrpt    9  70.999 ± 0.246  ops/s\r\n\r\n# Patched, CEA=32\r\nSerial.test  thrpt    9  73.991 ± 0.860  ops/s\r\n\r\n# Patched, CEA=128\r\nSerial.test  thrpt    9  72.981 ± 0.301  ops/s\r\n```\r\n\r\nAdditional testing:\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 fastdebug `tier1`\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 fastdebug `tier2`\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 fastdebug `tier3`\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284578](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284578): Relax InterpreterCodelet stub alignment\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Vladimir Kozlov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kvn) (@vnkozlov - **Reviewer**)\n * [Dean Long](https://openjdk.java.net/census#dlong) (@dean-long - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8159/head:pull/8159` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8159`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8159` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8159/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8159`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8159`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8159.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8159.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1164669878,"created_at":"2022-03-10T02:42:01Z","updated_at":"2022-05-10T06:34:08Z","state":"closed","title":"7124282: [macosx] Can't see table cell highlighter when the highlight border is the same color as the cell.","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/7768","body":"Previously while tabbing through the JTable cell, the cell highlighter/focus ring was not visible against the selection background. \r\n\r\nChanges are made to Aqua LAF to derive a lighter focus ring color by changing saturation and setting brightness component to 100% of original focus ring color so that it is visible while tabbing through `JTable` cells. A new method is added for this purpose which takes in `focusRingColor`, does adjustment to saturation and brightness and returns a new focus ring color. There are edge cases where the HSB transformation does not yield the right focus ring color, for these cases a default color is returned.\r\n\r\nA test case is added to compare the RGB difference between the original focus ring color & selection background and the new focus ring color & selection background. A note on the test case, since the test case is automated it tests the cell focus ring with colors loaded during the start of program execution and any on-the-fly accent color changes were tested manually.\r\n\r\n**Edge Cases**\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/95945681/161360456-3929acf1-282b-4c2b-95d1-1d5707c1e238.png)\r\n\r\nThe edge case condition consists of two parts –\r\n\r\n- To handle white/black colors - (hsbValues[0] == 0 && hsbValues[1] == 0) - representing hue and saturation of zero obtained for black, white or exactly grey (red=green=color) conditions\r\n\r\n\r\n- To handle grayish colors - hsbValues[1] <= satGrayScale where satGrayScale <= 0.10 . For any given hue and brightness, a saturation of less than or equal to 10% represents grayish tint colors. (The second case was added to accommodate grayish focus ring color returned by system when Accent color = Graphite.  The returned color is not exactly gray but grayish (r=135, g=135, b=140)). To accommodate a more generic case of grayish colors, the satGrayScale has a threshold or tolerance of 0.10 or 10%. \r\n\r\nUsed the following resources to test out different grayish colors and optimal saturation offsets used in  `deriveLighterFocusRing()`.\r\n\r\n- [RapidTables](https://www.rapidtables.com/convert/color/rgb-to-hsl.html) \r\n- [Colorizer](http://colorizer.org/).\r\n- [Chart Link](https://codepen.io/HunorMarton/details/eWvewo)\r\n\r\n**A note on the system-colors:** \r\n\r\n_For Mac 10.14 below:_\r\n[keyboardfocusindicatorcolor](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nscolor/1532031-keyboardfocusindicatorcolor)\r\nIssue: Works well for most of the scenarios (including on-the-fly changes) and follows the accent color changes except when we start the application with accent color set to Graphite and then change accent color on-the-fly The cell focus ring remains gray. The issue is with the system color returned by the type-property \"keyboardfocusindicatorcolor\" under this setting and NOT a JDK product bug.\r\n\r\n_For Mac 10.14+:_\r\n[controlAccentColor](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nscolor/3000782-controlaccentcolor)\r\nis available and it follows accent color changes (even when application started with Graphite as accent color). The proposed fix uses this type property when mac version is 10.14+\r\n\r\nPS: The native L&F (Mac OS) and Swing L&F for JTable cell tabbing differs (on native tables the cell background turns white on focus with a cell focus ring). Since the background for Swing tables can be set by users and also overridden by subclassing `DefaultTableCellRenderer`, and to adhere to current implementation of Swing, the white cell background changes are not incorporated. Only the Focus Ring/ Cell Highlighter is made more prominent.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed (1 review required, with at least 1 reviewer)\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-7124282](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-7124282): [macosx] Can't see table cell highlighter when the highlight border is the same color as the cell.\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Prasanta Sadhukhan](https://openjdk.java.net/census#psadhukhan) (@prsadhuk - **Reviewer**)\n * [Phil Race](https://openjdk.java.net/census#prr) (@prrace - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7768/head:pull/7768` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7768`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7768` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7768/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 7768`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 7768`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7768.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7768.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1195342739,"created_at":"2022-04-07T00:38:07Z","updated_at":"2022-04-20T17:02:55Z","state":"closed","title":"JDK-8281006 Module::getResourceAsStream should check if the resource is open unconditionally when caller is null","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8134","body":"Created a test called NullCallerGetResource to test Module::getResourceAsStream and Class::getResourceAsStream from the native level.\r\n\r\nAt the java level the test builds a test module called 'n' which opens the package 'open' to everyone. There is also a package 'closed' which is neither opened or exported. Both packages have a text file called 'test.txt'. The open package has a class called OpenResources and the closed package has a class called ClosedResources. The native test is launched with the test module n added.\r\n\r\nAt the native level the test tries to read both the open and closed resource from both the classes and the module. It performs the equivalent of the following java operations:\r\n\r\nClass c = open.OpenResources.fetchClass();\r\nInputStream in = c.getResourceAsStream(\"test.txt\");\r\nassert(in != null); in.close();\r\n\r\nModule n = c.getModule();\r\nin = n.getResourceAsStream(\"open/test.txt\");\r\nassert(in != null); in.close();\r\n\r\nClass closed = closed.ClosedResources.fetchClass();\r\nassert(closedsStream(\"test.txt\") == null);\r\nassert(n.getResourceAsStream(\"closed/test.txt\") == null);\r\n\r\nThe test initially threw an NPE when trying to fetch the open resource. The Module class was fixed by removing the fragment with the (caller == null) test in getResourceAsStream, and changing the call to isOpen(String,Module) to use EVERYONE_MODULE if the caller module is null.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8281006](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8281006): Module::getResourceAsStream should check if the resource is open unconditionally when caller is null\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Alan Bateman](https://openjdk.java.net/census#alanb) (@AlanBateman - **Reviewer**)\n * [Erik Joelsson](https://openjdk.java.net/census#erikj) (@erikj79 - **Reviewer**) ⚠️ Review applies to 4b344e4de98b9ccdd3ab49731599bf6bff11cfd8\n * [Mandy Chung](https://openjdk.java.net/census#mchung) (@mlchung - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8134/head:pull/8134` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8134`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8134` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8134/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8134`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8134`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8134.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8134.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1211879763,"created_at":"2022-04-22T06:26:01Z","updated_at":"2022-04-23T14:40:57Z","state":"closed","title":"8285431: Assertion in NativeGSSContext constructor","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8355","body":"Hi,\r\n\r\nMay I have the simple update reviewed.\r\n\r\nIn the NativeGSSContext constructor for imported context, the assert is use on the object field, instead of the input parameters. As in a constructor, `'this'` object does not exist yet, this looks like an obvious issue.  The fix is straightforward as well. \r\n\r\n```\r\n    NativeGSSContext(long pCtxt, GSSLibStub stub) throws GSSException {\r\n-       assert(pContext != 0);\r\n+       assert(pCtxt != 0);\r\n        pContext = pCtxt;\r\n        ...\r\n\r\n```\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8285431](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8285431): Assertion in NativeGSSContext constructor\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Daniel Jeliński](https://openjdk.java.net/census#djelinski) (@djelinski - Committer)\n * [Valerie Peng](https://openjdk.java.net/census#valeriep) (@valeriepeng - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8355/head:pull/8355` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8355`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8355` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8355/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8355`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8355`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8355.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8355.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1192275732,"created_at":"2022-04-04T20:24:44Z","updated_at":"2022-05-12T13:40:46Z","state":"closed","title":"8284283: javac crashes when several transitive supertypes are missing","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8095","body":"Consider this testcase:\r\n```\r\n---Lib.java\r\npackage lib;\r\npublic class Lib implements A, B {}\r\ninterface A {}\r\ninterface B {}\r\n---Test.java\r\npublic class Test<E> extends lib.Lib {}\r\n---\r\n\r\n$ javac -d out Lib.java\r\n$ rm out/lib/A.class out/lib/B.class\r\n$ javac -classpath out -XDdev Test.java\r\nTest.java:1: error: cannot access A\r\npublic class Test<E> extends lib.Lib {}\r\n       ^\r\n  class file for lib.A not found\r\n1 error\r\nAn exception has occurred in the compiler (17-internal). Please file a bug against the Java compiler via the Java bug reporting page (http://bugreport.java.com/) after checking the Bug Database (http://bugs.java.com/) for duplicates. Include your program, the following diagnostic, and the parameters passed to the Java compiler in your report. Thank you.\r\njava.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke \"com.sun.tools.javac.code.Type.hasTag(com.sun.tools.javac.code.TypeTag)\" because the return value of \"com.sun.tools.javac.code.Type$TypeVar.getUpperBound()\" is null\r\n        at jdk.compiler/com.sun.tools.javac.code.Types.getBounds(Types.java:2732)\r\n....\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe reason for the cache is insufficient error recovery - when the missing class `A` and `B` are encountered, the processing in `TypeEnter` (`TypeEnter.HierarchyPhase` for `A` and `TypeEnter.HeaderPhase` for `B`) is interrupted, and the rest of the processing is skipped to the end of the phase, leaving unprocessed tree, which ultimately leads to the exception.\r\n\r\nThe proposed patch is to enhance the error recovery, catch the `CompletionFailure` for the missing classes sooner, and let the rest of the `TypeEnter` processing finish normally.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284283](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284283): javac crashes when several transitive supertypes are missing\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Vicente Romero](https://openjdk.java.net/census#vromero) (@vicente-romero-oracle - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8095/head:pull/8095` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8095`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8095` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8095/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8095`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8095`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8095.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8095.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

deprecations (with a removal target of 3.6.0).<\/p>\n<h2>What's Changed<\/h2>\n<h2>:warning: Update considerations and deprecations<\/h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Deprecate CacheFlux and CacheMono, for removal in
