{"id":1220100853,"created_at":"2022-04-29T07:28:09Z","updated_at":"2022-05-19T07:46:46Z","state":"closed","title":"make shell scripts more strict","html_url":"https://github.com/opensearch-project/OpenSearch/issues/3106","body":"shell scripts by default skip over errors and continue. it's best practices to use [`set`](https://ss64.com/bash/set.html) to harden this using the following flags:\r\n* `-e`: Exit immediately if a command exits with a non-zero status.\r\n* `-u`: Treat unset variables as an error when substituting.\r\n* possibly also `-o pipefail`: If set, the return value of a pipeline is the value of the last (rightmost) command to exit with a non-zero status, or zero if all commands in the pipeline exit successfully. By default, pipelines only return a failure if the last command errors. When used in combination with set -e, pipefail will make a script exit if any command in a pipeline errors.\r\n\r\nso far i've used `set -eu`, but i've seen that OpenSearch has also used `set -e -o pipefail` (see example below).\r\n\r\ni think somebody with expert knowledge in this area (i wouldn't consider myself an expert here) should define the standard to be used in all scripts (or rules for when to use what if there are differentiating needs).\r\n\r\nsome scripts already have this set, e.g.:\r\nhttps://github.com/opensearch-project/OpenSearch/blob/c8ac0373895fe6b884792569029bdc9d465850b5/distribution/src/bin/opensearch-env#L3\r\n\r\nothers don't, e.g. https://github.com/opensearch-project/OpenSearch/blob/main/distribution/packages/src/deb/init.d/opensearch\r\n\r\nthis is relevant not just for this repository but for all repositories (i'm not aware of a meta-repository where to open such tickets, feel free to move this ticket if such a place exists).\r\n\r\nstandardising and applying this globally will ensure that errors are not (silently) hidden."}

{"id":1210003464,"created_at":"2022-04-20T17:40:24Z","updated_at":"2022-04-20T19:27:32Z","state":"closed","title":"8284920: Incorrect Token type causes XPath expression to return incorrect results","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8321","body":"Patch note:\r\n\r\nThe previous patch changed all literal tokens to use constants. However, replacing \".\" with Token.DOT introduced this bug. \r\nWhile tokens with a single char are inherently of type char, due to the different implementation of the overloaded method \"tokenIs\" that takes String or char, a wrong input type will produce incorrect result. It may be worth it to take a closer look at the overloaded method, but for now, a quick fix is to reverse the input type back to String (DOT_STR).\r\n\r\nTest: the issue affect the processing of the short form of the parent axis \"..\". The test verifies that all form of the parent axis shall return the same result.\r\n\r\nTest: all XML tests passed.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284920](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284920): Incorrect Token type causes XPath expression to return incorrect results ⚠️ Issue is not open.\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Naoto Sato](https://openjdk.java.net/census#naoto) (@naotoj - **Reviewer**)\n * [Lance Andersen](https://openjdk.java.net/census#lancea) (@LanceAndersen - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8321/head:pull/8321` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8321`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8321` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8321/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8321`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8321`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8321.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8321.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1208837657,"created_at":"2022-04-19T20:38:31Z","updated_at":"2022-04-21T08:41:25Z","state":"closed","title":"8285093: Introduce UTIL_ARG_WITH","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8306","body":"Analogous to `UTIL_ARG_ENABLE`, we need a `UTIL_ARG_WITH` which wraps ´AC_ARG_WITH`, provides a declarative rather than programmatic way of handling configure arguments. It can also make sure that all edge cases are covered, and that we treat arguments consistently. \r\n\r\nThis PR contains the implementation of `UTIL_ARG_WITH`, and an example conversation of the calls to `AC_ARG_WITH` in basic_tools.m4. There are some 120-odd more places where `AC_ARG_WITH` is called that need to be converted, but that is out of scope for this PR. Getting the m4 logic for `AC_ARG_WITH` was hard enough for this PR, and verifying a whole bunch of configure arguments is mind-numbingly boring. So I intend to attack those piecewise, fixing them in large enough batches at a time, later on.\r\n\r\nI also fixed a bug and a documentation issue in `UTIL_ARG_ENABLE`.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8285093](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8285093): Introduce UTIL_ARG_WITH\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Erik Joelsson](https://openjdk.java.net/census#erikj) (@erikj79 - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8306/head:pull/8306` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8306`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8306` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8306/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8306`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8306`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8306.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8306.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1206203655,"created_at":"2022-04-16T19:55:58Z","updated_at":"2022-04-27T17:38:29Z","state":"closed","title":"Transfer API improvements and breaking changes for 1.19","html_url":"https://github.com/FabricMC/fabric/pull/2139","body":"This PR aims to improve the transfer API after feedback from practical use.\r\n\r\nSince the transfer API is experimental, we reserve the right to make breaking changes. However, many mods rely on the transfer API staying stable, and it would be insane to break them at this stage. That's why this PR is only targeted at 1.19: I expect most mods to have to update already, so while these changes are going to be inconvenient, at least we won't break the ecosystem mid-release. The idea is for this PR to be merged before the first 1.19 pre-release drops.\r\n\r\nThis also means that the transfer API likely won't be stabilized before 1.20, as we might want to do another round of breaking changes in the 1.19 to 1.20 update.\r\n\r\n_Note to maintainers_: The transfer API version should be bumped to `2.0.0` after this PR is merged.\r\n\r\n## Changes\r\n### Remove deprecated APIs\r\nSelf-explanatory. Cleanup of existing deprecated APIs. Since there might be many more iterations of the transfer API, we shouldn't let these clutter the place.\r\n\r\n### Remove the transaction requirement for storage iterator\r\nIt turns out that the transaction parameter doesn't seem useful in practice (the use case it was intended for can be done in other ways). Removing the parameter makes the API less akward, since `Storage<T>` now implements `Iterable<StorageView<T>>`. The `iterator(TransactionContext)` and `iterable(TransactionContext)` are removed.\r\nIteration is now easier: `for (StorageView<T> view : storage) {` instead of `for (StorageView<T> view : storage.iterable(transaction)) {`\r\nFixes #2003.\r\n\r\n### Allow client-side API queries for existence checks\r\nTo check whether a block exposes a `Storage` on the client-side, for example to decide if a block might be supported or if the player hand should swing, it's often a lot easier to perform a `find(...) != null` check on the client, even if it might be incorrect in some edge cases, than to perform the query on the server and wait for its response.\r\n\r\nHence, querying storages on the client-side is now allowed for existence checks, however it should be noted that their contents are unreliable.\r\n\r\n### (Not breaking) Introduce `SidedStorageBlockEntity` for easier Storage registration\r\nMany mods already roll their own similar interface, so we make it easier for them by providing a straightforward helper.\r\n\r\n### (Not breaking) Improve SnapshotParticipant javadoc\r\nHopefully this makes `SnapshotParticipant` a little bit easier to understand."}

{"id":1079337526,"created_at":"2021-12-14T05:44:17Z","updated_at":"2022-03-23T09:59:07Z","state":"closed","title":"8278348: [macos12] javax/swing/JTree/4908142/bug4908142.java fails in macos12","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/6826","body":"Test seem to be failing in macos12.0.1 (although it does not seem to affect 12.1) due to keypresses of \"a\", \"a\", \"d\" is not selecting \"aad\" but \"ade\" which seems to point to the fact that 2 exclusive \"a\" keypress are considered as 1 \"a\" keypress.\r\nAlthough I am not able to reroduce this issue if test is ran standalone or in JTree group, but it fails when ran as toplevel \"jdk_desktop\" testgroup or even whole swing test group.\r\n\r\nLooking at text navigational algorithm probably done in JDK-4908142 (although I am not sure if this is done for that bug or subsequently revised) \r\nhttps://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.desktop/share/classes/javax/swing/plaf/basic/BasicTreeUI.java#L3804\r\n\r\nit seems if a subsequent key press comes after a predefined timefactor after the previous keypress, it is considered as a fresh/new keypress and not part of ongoing string search ie, if 2nd \"a\" comes after the predefined timefactor from 1st \"a', then seacrh algorithm will search for \"ad\" and not \"aad\" as can be seen here\r\nhttps://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.desktop/share/classes/javax/swing/plaf/basic/BasicTreeUI.java#L3815\r\n\r\nI am not sure why macos12 will take so long  for 2nd \"a\" keypress  but the logs corraborates that it does take more than \"timefactor\" time what is set now, which is 1000.\r\n1st \"a\" keypress, we have time 1639400688049 lastTime 0 typedString a\r\n2nd \"a\" keypress, we have time 1639400691150 lastTime 1639400688049 typedString a [which is diff of 3101]\r\n\r\nSo, proposed fix is to configure \"Tree.timeFactor\" to 5000 to workaround this macos12 issue. It pass when full desktop tests is run in macos12 and also test passes in all platforms.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [ ] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8278348](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8278348): [macos12] javax/swing/JTree/4908142/bug4908142.java fails in macos12\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/6826/head:pull/6826` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/6826`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/6826` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/6826/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 6826`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 6826`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/6826.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/6826.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

Please describe.**\r\n\r\n- Lots of help requests are lost when help requests 'time out' after an hour (especially the more technical / difficult (not amateur) questions.\r\n- Often there are not enough channels for the volume of help requests recieved\r\n- Often the current channel breakup (6 channels for basic java, 3 channels for frameworks, 2 channels for swing/javaFX, etc) is incorrect for current needs\r\n\r\n**Describe the solution you'd like**\r\nEnhance the existing Help System to use threads:\r\n- Instead of a status showing busy/free channels change the status display to show open help requests (linked to the relevant thread) which are tagged to show the relevant experince needed to answer the questions. Some example tags would be: `Mooc`, `Spring Boot`, `Spring`,  `JDBC`, `MongoDb`, `MySQL`, `swing`, `javaFX` etc\r\n- Create a 'form' for users to use to open a thread and ask their question (this will prevent spamming channels / spamming new thread creations, allow the system to monitor existing channels, etc)\r\n- Allow top helpers (current and previous) / Moderators and maybe other roles to add tags, modify title, etc for help requests\r\n- Allow others to try change title, tags etc of the request but only with the OP's confirmation\r\n"}

{"id":1185355180,"created_at":"2022-03-29T20:06:26Z","updated_at":"2022-04-03T15:23:06Z","state":"closed","title":"Form UI Freeze for some maintenance screens","html_url":"https://github.com/blueseerERP/blueseer/issues/49","body":"The UI Form for several maintenance screen will freeze after several cycles of get / update fetch.   The time to freeze is random.   This is a result of the Version 6 refactor effort.   The get, add, update, delete routines are executed via an independent SwingWorker thread.   Some of these routines have UI form fields and/or lang pack labels that are 'refreshed' in the scope of this thread that don't play well with the main Swing EDT (Event dispatch thread)...and as such will cause undesirable effects (freezes).    The solution is to move 'all' UI form field refreshes out of this thread and call/set from within the 'Done()' routine."}

{"id":1223457687,"created_at":"2022-05-02T23:20:52Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T19:47:26Z","state":"closed","title":"8284027: vmTestbase/nsk/jvmti/GetAllThreads/allthr001/ is failing","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8512","body":"The test counts all \"system\" threads before the execution and expects that this number remains the same during test execution.\r\nThis makes the test fragile - JVM may start internal threads, some threads may end.\r\n\r\nThe fix updates the test:\r\n- the test checks only test threads, and verify that the live threads are reported by GetAllThreads and terminated threads are not reported;\r\n- dropped \"system\" thread counting stuff;\r\n- added proper deallocation of GetThreadInfo results.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! {"id":1129453585,"created_at":"2022-02-10T04:59:33Z","updated_at":"2022-03-12T14:35:29Z","state":"closed","title":"8277922: Unable to click JCheckBox in JTable through Java Access Bridge","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/7416","body":"Hello,\r\n\r\nCould you please review the following fix for the bug. The bug consists in the fact that When an assistive technology software by means of Java Access Bridge API executes \"AccessibleAction\" \"click\" on \"AccessibleContext\" which corresponds to \"javax.swing.JTable\" cell containing \"javax.swing.JCheckBox\", then the cell's value and cell's view represented by \"JCheckBox\" stay unchanged. The issue is a bug in JDK and should be fixed in JDK, because JDK informs the assistive technology software through Java Access Bridge API in particular through the function\r\n\r\n\"BOOL getAccessibleActions(long vmID, AccessibleContext accessibleContext, AccessibleActions *actions)\"\r\n\r\nthat \"AccessibleContext\" of the table cell with \"JCheckBox\" supports one action \"click\", while real execution of this action on this accessible context does not lead to any result.\r\n\r\nTHE ROOT CAUSE OF THE BUG:\r\n\r\nThe reason of the issue is the fact that when the assistive technology software tries to do \"AccessibleAction\" on \"AccessibleContext\" associated with a cell with boolean data type in \"JTable\" component through Java Access Bridge (JAB), the JDK executes this \"AccessibleAction\" on \"AccessibleContext\" of a renderer, which is an instance of the class \"javax.swing.JTable.BooleanRenderer\" which is a derivative of \"JCheckBox\" class, and the instance of this renderer is single and common for all cells of boolean data type. Therefore execution of \"click\" \"AccessibleAction\" on this renderer component which is not permanently bound to any particular cell in the table does not lead to update of the table cell value.\r\n\r\nTHE FIX:\r\n\r\nThe fix implements an approach which guarantees setting of new values to the table's cells with boolean data type on each execution of \"AccessibleAction\" of \"javax.swing.JTable.BooleanRenderer\" instance, when execution of this action changes the \"selected\" state of this \"BooleanRenderer\" JCheckBox component.\r\n\r\nPlease take into account that the created automatic regression test simulates the issue only with Java Accessibility API what is not fully equal to the original test scenario which requires the assistive technology software and usage of Java Access Bridge API and which can be tested using the manual test case attached to the issue in JBS. However the regression test still allows to reproduce the issue and verify that the fix resolves it.\r\n\r\nThank you,\r\nAnton\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8277922](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8277922): Unable to click JCheckBox in JTable through Java Access Bridge\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Alexey Ivanov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#aivanov) (@aivanov-jdk - **Reviewer**)\n * [Sergey Bylokhov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#serb) (@mrserb - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7416/head:pull/7416` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7416`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7416` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7416/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 7416`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 7416`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7416.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7416.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1190978324,"created_at":"2022-04-03T16:30:07Z","updated_at":"2022-05-24T22:01:07Z","state":"closed","title":"[tado] Fix AC control bugs; Add null annotations and checks","html_url":"https://github.com/openhab/openhab-addons/pull/12570","body":"Fixes #12552 \r\n\r\nIn PR #12470 the reviewer @jlaur remarked that the new code was missing @NonNullByDefault tags, and therefore lacking the proper potential NPE validation checks. I added that this applies not only to the new code, but also to the whole binding. So for those reasons I opened issue #12552..\r\n\r\nThis PR resolves that issue as follows..\r\n- Added @NonNullByDefault tags to all human created classes; (impossible on the Swagger generated classes).\r\n- On the majority of variables/fields thus asserted to be @NonNull -- deleted the redundant null checks.\r\n- On the few variables/fields that had to remain @Nullable -- added null checks and NPE avoidance code.\r\n- Added `final` on fields created in the constructor.\r\n- If the API returns a null state value, the respective channel (if any) is now updated with a `UndefType.UNDEF` state.\r\n- Added `default` throw code on `switch` statements that map API enum's to binding enum's (will cause exceptions in case the API enum's might be extended, but the binding enum's are not).\r\n- Eliminated all other remaining compiler warnings on the human created classes; (impossible on the Swagger generated classes).\r\n- Eliminated \"Bridge not initialized\" exception resp. log warning on shutdown.\r\n\r\nNote that the Tado REST API schema has many JSON fields where, (depending on the type of Tado device, and its respective state), the JSON elements may be either missing or null. So the Swagger generated API DTO classes must NOT have @NonNullByDefault. And therefore the 'trick' in this PR is to ensure that the data transfer between @Nullable API classes and @NonNullByDefault human created classes has not broken anything. => Further testing by a few Tado device owners is requested!\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nEDIT: @Freeride79 also reported some bugs related to the new features introduced in PR #12470, so this PR also addresses and fixes those bugs..\r\n- Checks if new command state values are in the device's reported capabilities list of supported values. This is now checked before sending the command to the server. A warning is logged if the value is not supported.\r\n- When sending new overlay commands, the binding replaces any null values by either a) the last known value, or b) the first value listed in the capabilities list.\r\n- Improved trace logging of JSON payloads. And if the remote server reports an HTTP 429 or 409 error, the respective JSON command payload will be output to logger.warn()\r\n- Fixed bugs in #12470 code"}

{"id":1211314602,"created_at":"2022-04-21T17:02:27Z","updated_at":"2022-05-19T09:54:15Z","state":"closed","title":"8285394: Compiler blackholes can be eliminated due to stale ciMethod::intrinsic_id()","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8344","body":"This is seen in some tests: if blackhole method is deemed hot for inlining, then at least C2 would inline it without looking back at its intrinsic status. Which silently breaks blackholes.\r\n\r\nThe cause is that there are *two* places where intrinsic ID is recorded. Current blackhole code only writes down blackhole intrinsic ID in `Method::intrinsic_id()`, but we should also set it in `ciMethod::intrinsic_id()`, which is used from C2 inlining code. `ciMethod` is normally populated from `Method::intrinsic_id()`, but it happens too early, before setting up blackhole intrinsic. \r\n\r\nAdditional testing:\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 {fastdebug,release}, wew test fails before the patch, passes with it\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 {fastdebug,release} `compiler/blackhole`\r\n - [x] Linux x86_64 fastdebug, sanity microbenchmark corpus run with the patch\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8285394](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8285394): Compiler blackholes can be eliminated due to stale ciMethod::intrinsic_id()\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Vladimir Kozlov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kvn) (@vnkozlov - **Reviewer**)\n * [Dean Long](https://openjdk.java.net/census#dlong) (@dean-long - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8344/head:pull/8344` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8344`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8344` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8344/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8344`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8344`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8344.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8344.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}
{"id":1137984144,"created_at":"2022-02-14T23:48:03Z","updated_at":"2022-03-17T06:15:59Z","state":"closed","title":"Linux Processing 4.0b5 export application broken","html_url":"https://github.com/processing/processing4/issues/410","body":"<!--- ** For coding questions, please use https://forum.processing.org ** -->\r\n<!--- ** This form is only for bugs in the software & feature requests ** -->\r\n\r\n<!--- ** Also be sure to read the troubleshooting page first: ** -->\r\n<!--- ** https://github.com/processing/processing/wiki/Troubleshooting ** -->\r\n\r\n<!--- ** Before posting, please search Issues for duplicates  ** --> \r\n\r\n## Description\r\nUsing export application on Linux Processing 4.0b5 (Java) crashes with exception\r\n<!--- Use a title that describes what is happening. -->\r\n<!--- Give a description of the proposed change. -->\r\n\r\n## Expected Behavior\r\nIt should export a standalone application.\r\n<!--- Bug? {"id":1202051984,"created_at":"2022-04-12T15:56:15Z","updated_at":"2022-04-14T09:31:53Z","state":"closed","title":"8284760: Correct type/array element offset in LibraryCallKit::get_state_from_digest_object()","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8208","body":"In LibraryCallKit::get_state_from_digest_object() we call array_element_address() with T_INT, even though the input array might also be T_BYTE or T_LONG. This doesn't currently matter much: array elements always start at the same offset regardless of the element type. In Lilliput I'm trying to tighten the start of array elements though, and this causes problems because I can do smaller alignments for T_BYTE and T_INT, but not for T_LONG.\r\n\r\nSee also: https://github.com/openjdk/lilliput/pull/41\r\n\r\nLet's just use the correct type in array_element_address().\r\n\r\nTesting:\r\n - [x] tier1\r\n - [x] jdk_security (includes relevant cipher tests)\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284760](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284760): Correct type/array element offset in LibraryCallKit::get_state_from_digest_object()\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Roland Westrelin](https://openjdk.java.net/census#roland) (@rwestrel - **Reviewer**)\n * [Vladimir Kozlov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kvn) (@vnkozlov - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8208/head:pull/8208` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8208`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8208` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8208/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8208`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8208`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8208.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8208.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1153952075,"created_at":"2022-02-28T11:05:34Z","updated_at":"2022-03-11T15:05:45Z","state":"closed","title":"Deprecating reactor-extra's Swing/SwtScheduler (removal in 3.6.0)","html_url":"https://github.com/reactor/reactor-addons/issues/273","body":"### Motivation\r\nThe `SwingScheduler` and `SwtScheduler` adapters don't seem to have much traction, as far as we're aware.\r\nThe SWT one is using outdated SWT libraries and complexifies the build infrastructure for little gain.\r\n\r\n(for instance, searching for `reactor.swing.SwingScheduler` results in 2 code hits in all of GitHub. The other one gets 3 hits total...)\r\n\r\n### Deprecation and removal plan\r\n1. Deprecation in 3.4.7 (estimated early March 2022)\r\n2. Removal in 3.6.0 (no planned date, probably late 2023 or late 2024)\r\n~2. Removal in 3.5.0 (estimated last quarter of 2022)~ (see comment below)\r\n\r\n### Additional steps\r\n - [ ] Remove from reference guide appendix in core (this seems to be the main source of results when searching for `SwtScheduler` in all of GitHub btw) => https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/pull/2959\r\n - [ ] Deprecate in parallel the corresponding extensions in `reactor-kotlin-extensions` => reactor/reactor-kotlin-extensions#38\r\n - [ ] Earlier removal of the very simple extension in `reactor-kotlin-extensions` 1.2.0 (see also reactor/reactor-kotlin-extensions#38)"}

{"id":1217844979,"created_at":"2022-04-27T20:23:32Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T20:00:24Z","state":"closed","title":"8272352: Java launcher can not parse Chinese character when system locale is set to UTF-8","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8434","body":"Java runtime has been detecting the Windows system locale encoding using `GetLocaleInfo(GetSystemDefaultLCID(), LOCALE_IDEFAULTANSICODEPAGE, ...)`, but it returns the *legacy* ANSI code page value, e.g, 1252 for US-English. In order to detect whether the user has selected `UTF-8` as the default, the code page has to be queried with `GetACP()`.\r\nAlso, the case if the call to `GetLocaleInfo` fails changed to fall back to `UTF-8` instead of `Cp1252`.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed (1 review required, with at least 1 reviewer)\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8272352](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8272352): Java launcher can not parse Chinese character when system locale is set to UTF-8\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Roger Riggs](https://openjdk.java.net/census#rriggs) (@RogerRiggs - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8434/head:pull/8434` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8434`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8434` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8434/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8434`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8434`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8434.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8434.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1037375321,"created_at":"2021-10-27T12:42:50Z","updated_at":"2022-03-07T18:02:57Z","state":"closed","title":"8276058: Some swing test fails on specific CI macos system","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/6140","body":"As per JDK-8252813, some tests fails recurringly in CI macos system. This is an attempt to fix the swing tests.\r\nIt was seen from the logs that we have color mismatch in these tests.\r\n\r\nFor example, in PressedIcon test, we had following log\r\n\r\n----------System.out:(1/75)----------\r\ncolor java.awt.Color[r=55,g=55,b=55] COLOR_1Xjava.awt.Color[r=255,g=0,b=0]\r\n----------System.err:(13/842)----------\r\njava.lang.RuntimeException: Colors is different for scale=1!\r\n\tat PressedIconTest.main(PressedIconTest.java:97)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:76)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:51)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:569)\r\n\tat com.sun.javatest.regtest.agent.MainWrapper$MainThread.run(MainWrapper.java:127)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:833)\r\n\r\nand JInternalFrame test, we had \r\n----------System.err:(15/939)----------\r\nFRAME_COLOR Red: 255; Green: 200; Blue: 0\r\nPixel color Red: 55; Green: 55; Blue: 55\r\njava.lang.RuntimeException: Internal frame is not correctly dragged!\r\n\tat bug8069348.main(bug8069348.java:96)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:76)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:51)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:569)\r\n\tat com.sun.javatest.regtest.agent.MainWrapper$MainThread.run(MainWrapper.java:127)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:833)\r\n\r\nwhere color is obtained as 55,55,55 instead of required color. The png image generated at failure also did not reveal anything abnormal apart from presence of mouse cursor around the same area where the getPixelColor location is pointing to. And since mouse cursor is also grayish black, it seems robot was wrongly picking up cursor pixels instead of background color.\r\nModified tests to use location.x-10, location.y-10 to obtain the pixel color. It does not hamper the test as the whole area around the location is coloured with same color in the test so getting pixel color from a bit wide of the centre will not affect the test.\r\nModified swing tests are passing in the affected system and also in other macos systems and platforms. Link in JBS.\r\n\r\nThe awt tests that are failing seems to have different root cause and will be handled separately.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8276058](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8276058): Some swing test fails on specific CI macos system\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Phil Race](https://openjdk.java.net/census#prr) (@prrace - **Reviewer**)\n * [Alexander Zuev](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kizune) (@azuev-java - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/6140/head:pull/6140` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/6140`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/6140` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/6140/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 6140`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 6140`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/6140.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/6140.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

So far, the use of nmethod entry barriers has implied that nmethod oops are patched in the instruction stream. That is no longer the case. A condition was added to make sure we still get non-immediate oops on AArch64 for collectors that use nmethod entry barriers, and support immediate oops. However, the condition was messed up, so we instead end up doing the wrong thing. {"id":1121692765,"created_at":"2022-02-02T09:30:29Z","updated_at":"2022-02-02T09:51:56Z","state":"closed","title":"Hide top-level dialog from the taskbar","html_url":"https://github.com/JetBrains/androidx/pull/177","body":"Swing has a special constructor for that (without arguments). It says:\r\n```\r\nA shared, hidden frame will be set as the owner of the dialog.\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe need exactly this as a default behaviour for top-level Dialog's. This will hide the icon in the taskbar. If the user need to show icon in the taskbar, Window is a better option.\r\n\r\nIf `SwingUtilities.getSharedOwnerFrame()` was public, I would just use it as a default value in the constructor, but instead we have to create a separate constructor and keep it consistent with `JDialog`, even if it is unusual API.\r\n\r\nThe reproducer:\r\n```\r\nimport androidx.compose.ui.awt.ComposeDialog\r\nimport javax.swing.SwingUtilities\r\n\r\nfun main() = SwingUtilities.invokeLater {\r\n    val dialog = ComposeDialog()\r\n    dialog.setSize(800, 600)\r\n    dialog.isVisible = true\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe icon shouldn't be in the taskbar now.\r\n\r\nOld behavior:\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5963351/152127666-46f17aa4-d2b6-4313-b315-abbffd0fb837.png)\r\n\r\nNew behavior:\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5963351/152127706-8716218c-07f4-4dc7-ada1-4a1a802f88b8.png)\r\n\r\n"}
{"id":1042004718,"created_at":"2021-11-02T08:17:23Z","updated_at":"2022-03-29T09:42:04Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove OpenJFX dependencies while publishing to mvncentral","html_url":"https://github.com/palexdev/MaterialFX/pull/116","body":"Currently when you add the project as a dependency to any maven project, you get the following IDE error:\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25760501/139809363-d8a3e29d-00a3-4533-8b13-973cf0d3df19.png)\r\n\r\nThis is happening because the dependency MaterialFX is providing javafx dependencies, that should not be happening. Hence a workaround I am using is to add the following exclusions in my `pom.xml`:\r\n\r\n```XML\r\n<dependency>\r\n  <groupId>io.github.palexdev<\/groupId>\r\n  <artifactId>materialfx<\/artifactId>\r\n  <version>${materialfx.version}<\/version>\r\n  <exclusions>\r\n    <exclusion>\r\n       <groupId>org.openjfx<\/groupId>\r\n       <artifactId>javafx-graphics<\/artifactId>\r\n    <\/exclusion>\r\n    <exclusion>\r\n      <groupId>org.openjfx<\/groupId>\r\n      <artifactId>javafx-controls<\/artifactId>\r\n    <\/exclusion>\r\n    <exclusion>\r\n       <groupId>org.openjfx<\/groupId>\r\n       <artifactId>javafx-base<\/artifactId>\r\n    <\/exclusion>\r\n    <exclusion>\r\n      <groupId>org.openjfx<\/groupId>\r\n      <artifactId>javafx-swing<\/artifactId>\r\n    <\/exclusion>\r\n  <\/exclusions>\r\n<\/dependency>\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis PR removes the OpenJFX dependencies before publishing, hence solving the issue.\r\n"}

{"id":1215964612,"created_at":"2022-04-26T13:31:00Z","updated_at":"2022-04-27T11:29:22Z","state":"closed","title":"JDK-8285675: Temporary fix for arm32 SafeFetch","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8399","body":"[JDK-8283326](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8283326) reworked the SafeFetch implementation and, on most platforms, switched to static assembly.\r\n\r\nOn arm (32-bit), this change led to strange crashes ([JDK-8284997](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284997)). These problems are time consuming to analyze (among other things they only occur when building natively on a Rasberry Pi with one particular Docker setup).\r\n\r\nAs a temporary workaround I'd like to switch SafeFetch to the sigjmp method for arm, until I find time to analyze these problems in more detail.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8285675](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8285675): Temporary fix for arm32 SafeFetch\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Martin Doerr](https://openjdk.java.net/census#mdoerr) (@TheRealMDoerr - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8399/head:pull/8399` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8399`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8399` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8399/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8399`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8399`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8399.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8399.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

Sometimes, however, the syntax parser actually fails. For me, this always manifests itself in the same way: starting from some  line in the middle of the file, every line below it is highlighted as a comment. I can fix this by going to the last line that isn't highlighted as a comment, commenting it out, and then uncommenting it. This always corrects the syntax highlighting for the rest of the file.\r\n\r\nImageJ 1.51t, Fiji Distribution, Java 1.8.0_66 (64-bit)"}

{"id":1134909524,"created_at":"2022-02-13T01:03:51Z","updated_at":"2022-04-06T20:28:48Z","state":"closed","title":"Add \"package\" build target","html_url":"https://github.com/openrocket/openrocket/pull/1128","body":"This adds a new ant build target, \"package\".  This target builds a .exe (on Windows), .dmg (on Mac), or appImage (on Linux), in the toplevel directory of the source tree.  This is now the default build target (so just 'ant' will build the appropriate package).  The jar file build along the way to the package is left in swing/build/jar/OpenRocket.jar, as before.  Alternatively, it is possible to run 'ant jar' and just create the jar file.\r\n\r\nThe Linux appImage target requires an extra program, appimagetool.AppImage, to execute.  Attempting the build under Linux without obtaining the the tool will cause instructions for obtaining it to be printed.\r\n\r\nIt has only been tested under Linux so far.  An appimage created using the tool can be found at https://drive.google.com/file/d/1oEDHbFWmM_SvQMGaSkUZ9qBmotNYerVN/view?usp=sharing\r\n\r\nThe Windows and Mac versions should (I hope!) be ready to go.  The Linux version requires some extra massaging of some metadata, but I wanted to make it available for testing early.  "}

{"id":1207630264,"created_at":"2022-04-19T02:12:09Z","updated_at":"2022-04-30T07:39:46Z","state":"closed","title":"8284981: Support the vectorization of some counting-down loops in SLP","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8289","body":"SLP can vectorize basic counting-down or counting-up loops. But for the counting-down loop below, in which array index scale\r\nis negative and index starts from a constant value, SLP can't succeed in vectorizing.\r\n\r\n```\r\n  private static final int SIZE = 2345;\r\n  private static int[] a = new int[SIZE];\r\n  private static int[] b = new int[SIZE];\r\n\r\n  public static void bar() {\r\n      for (int i = 1000; i > 0; i--) {\r\n          b[SIZE - i] = a[SIZE - i];\r\n      }\r\n  }\r\n```\r\n\r\nGenerally, it's necessary to find adjacent memory operations, i.e. load/store, after unrolling in SLP. Constructing SWPointers[1] for all memory operations is a key step to determine if these memory operations are adjacent. To construct a SWPointer successfully, SLP should first recognize the pattern of the memory address and normalize it. The address pattern of the memory operations in the case above can be visualized as:\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39403138/163905008-e9d62a4a-74f1-4d05-999b-8c4d5fc84d2b.png)\r\nwhich is equivalent to `(N - (long) i) << 2`. SLP recursively resolves the address mode by SWPointer::scaled_iv_plus_offset(). When arriving at the `SubL` node, it accepts `SubI` only and finally rejects the pattern of the case above[2]. In this way, SLP can't construct effective SWPointers for these memory operations and the process of vectorization breaks off.\r\n\r\nThe pattern like `(N - (long) i) << 2` is formal and easy to resolve. We add the pattern of SubL in the patch to vectorize counting-down loops like the case above.\r\n\r\nAfter the patch, generated loop code for above case is like below on\r\naarch64:\r\n```\r\nLOOP: mov   w10, w12\r\n      sxtw  x12, w10\r\n      neg   x0, x12\r\n      lsl   x0, x0, #2\r\n      add   x1, x17, x0\r\n      ldr   q16, [x1, x2]\r\n      add   x0, x18, x0\r\n      str   q16, [x0, x2]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x1, x13]\r\n      str   q16, [x0, x13]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x1, x14]\r\n      str   q16, [x0, x14]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x1, x15]\r\n      sub   x12, x11, x12\r\n      lsl   x12, x12, #2\r\n      add   x3, x17, x12\r\n      str   q16, [x0, x15]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x3, x2]\r\n      add   x12, x18, x12\r\n      str   q16, [x12, x2]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x1, x16]\r\n      str   q16, [x0, x16]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x3, x14]\r\n      str   q16, [x12, x14]\r\n      ldr   q16, [x3, x15]\r\n      str   q16, [x12, x15]\r\n      sub   w12, w10, #0x20\r\n      cmp   w12, #0x1f\r\n      b.gt  LOOP\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis patch also works on x86 simd machines. We tested full jtreg on both aarch64 and x86 platforms. All tests passed.\r\n\r\n[1] https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/b56df2808d79dcc1e2d954fe38dd84228c683e8b/src/hotspot/share/opto/superword.cpp#L3826\r\n[2] https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/b56df2808d79dcc1e2d954fe38dd84228c683e8b/src/hotspot/share/opto/superword.cpp#L3953\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284981](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284981): Support the vectorization of some counting-down loops in SLP\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Roland Westrelin](https://openjdk.java.net/census#roland) (@rwestrel - **Reviewer**) ⚠️ Review applies to 0ee87952bbce81255ccf316c6420130e97b5534d\n * [Vladimir Kozlov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#kvn) (@vnkozlov - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8289/head:pull/8289` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8289`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8289` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8289/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8289`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8289`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8289.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8289.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1184472794,"created_at":"2022-03-29T08:04:42Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T04:22:19Z","state":"closed","title":"8283245: Create a test for JDK-4670319","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8012","body":"Write an automated regression test for  JDK-4670319\r\n\r\nIssue\r\nWhen a JTree node is expanded or collapsed, an Accessibility PropertyChange event is fired with the old state of \"collapsed\" and new state of \"expanded\" (or vice versa). The problem is that the source of the event is the AccessibeJTree, and not the AccessibleJTreeNode. This means that an assistive technology listening to this event is unable to report to the user what node was expanded/collapsed.\r\n\r\nFix\r\nFix for [JDK-4670319](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-4670319) addresses the above issue.  When tree node is expanded/collapsed, PropertyChangeEventSource is the Node.\r\nThis review is for a test for validating the above issue.\r\n\r\nThis review is for migrating tests from a closed test suite to open.\r\n\r\nTesting:\r\nThe test ran successfully on Mach5 with multiple runs (30) on windows-x64, linux-x64 and macos-x64.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8283245](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8283245): Create a test for JDK-4670319\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Sergey Bylokhov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#serb) (@mrserb - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8012/head:pull/8012` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8012`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8012` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8012/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8012`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8012`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8012.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8012.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

If there is a Car (from OperationsPro) associated with this tag, the Road name and Car number are shown. The location and Track are shown in ComboBoxes which the user can set and then click on a button to set to the new Location and Track. Another button shows the Car in the Edit Car window. If there is no associated car, a button opens a window with a list of Road names. The user can select a road name and the second list shows all car numbers for that road. Once a car number has been selected a button sets the tag in that Car. By default the only visible road names and numbers are for cars that do not have a tag. A checkbox shows all cars, including those with tags.\r\n\r\nThe window is opened from the \"RFID\" menu choice (there is one for each RFID connection. The first choice opens the standard Serial Monitor Pane. This new Pane is opened from the second choice. The help screen can be viewed from the monitor pane, or I added a link in the Hardware RFID connection frame."}

{"id":1211725276,"created_at":"2022-04-22T02:02:01Z","updated_at":"2022-04-22T23:49:28Z","state":"closed","title":"8285303: riscv: Incorrect register mask in call_native_base","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8353","body":"In `MacroAssembler::call_native_base`, t0 and xmethod should be saved as expected:\r\n\r\n```cpp\r\nvoid MacroAssembler::call_native_base(address entry_point, Label *retaddr) {\r\n  Label E, L;\r\n  int32_t offset = 0;\r\n  push_reg(0x80000040, sp); // push << t0 & xmethod >> to sp\r\n  movptr_with_offset(t0, entry_point, offset);\r\n  jalr(x1, t0, offset);\r\n  if (retaddr != NULL) {\r\n    bind(*retaddr);\r\n  }\r\n  pop_reg(0x80000040, sp); // pop << t0 & xmethod >> from sp\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nRegister mask of '0x80000040' operates << t1 & xmethod >> here, which should be '0x80000020' for << t0 & xmethod >>.\r\n\r\nThis PR also removes `MacroAssembler::call_native_base` and `MacroAssembler::call_native_base`, expands the definitions of `call_native_base` to `MacroAssembler::call_VM_leaf_base` directly.\r\n\r\nLinux RISCV64 release hotspot/jdk tier1 tests are passed on QEMU.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! {"id":939503729,"created_at":"2021-07-08T06:06:30Z","updated_at":"2022-04-29T06:36:17Z","state":"closed","title":"Update default Tooltips in Frame5 to support HTML and show instantly.","html_url":"https://github.com/RPTools/maptool/issues/2850","body":"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**\r\nIn the old frame, the default tooltip was really quite nice.  It displayed instantly and supported HTML.  The default tooltip in frame5 takes a second or two to pop up (too long) and does not support even basic HTML (plain text only with no word wrap.)  That makes the default frame5 tooltip a significant downgrade (to the point of being kind of useless.)\r\n\r\n![frame5 tooltips](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/37131742/124869503-4f60e680-df8f-11eb-949e-4252b531f6b5.jpg)\r\n\r\n**Describe the solution you'd like**\r\nI would very much like it to mimic the old frame styling and features (html, wordwrap, and frame break) for both compatibility and usability.  \r\n\r\n**Describe alternatives you've considered**\r\nFrame5 allows you to make your own CSS tooltips but they have significant limitations.  First, I haven't found one that will break the element it's in (like a cell or a table or the frame5 boundry if outside a table.)  This is a HUGE limitation compared to what the old frame tooltip AND (for that matter) what the current default frame tooltip can do.  Second, forcing users to do this isn't very nice and contributes to gating another MT feature to requiring \"coding knowledge.\"  It's not enough to learn how to create the tooltip, you've now got to learn CSS (and even that isn't enough... see below.)\r\n\r\n**Additional context**\r\nHere is another screenshot showsing a basic HTML table in the old frame (left) versus in the new frame (right.)  Not the best table but I wanted it to be basic.  In both examples, the table pops up when you hover on the word \"Free\".  If I build that same table using a CSS tooltip it won't work because the word \"Free\" is in a table cell and the tooltip is limited by the width of that cell/element and won't expand across the frame (and definitely not the frame.)  So, as is, now we can't even use a decent tooltip in tables.\r\n\r\n![frame5 garbage tooltip](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/37131742/124870360-94394d00-df90-11eb-8bbe-20fd45da18e9.jpg)\r\n"}

{"id":1105558659,"created_at":"2022-01-17T09:04:42Z","updated_at":"2022-02-13T13:02:07Z","state":"closed","title":"[Bug 63620] Fix GUI freeze when viewing response body with long lines","html_url":"https://github.com/apache/jmeter/pull/694","body":"GUI gets unresponsive when the response contains long lines (e.g lines exceeding 100K chars).\r\nThe workaround is to add artificial line breaks.\r\n\r\nhttps://bz.apache.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=63620\r\n\r\nWe try to break on word boundaries first, and if not possible,\r\nwe break on char boundaries (e.g. large chunks of base64 data).\r\n\r\n```\r\nview.results.tree.max_line_size=110000 (defaults to 110K)\r\nview.results.tree.soft_wrap_line_size=100000 (defaults to max_line_size/1.1)\r\n```\r\n\r\nFor the reference, using [zero-width space](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-width_space) does not solve the problem, so I use `\\n` for breaking lines.\r\n\r\nCPU spin trace looks as follows:\r\n\r\n```\r\n\"AWT-EventQue...\r\n...\r\n        at sun.font.GlyphLayout.layout(Unknown Source)\r\n...\r\n        at java.awt.font.TextLine.<init>(Unknown Source)\r\n        at java.awt.font.TextMeasurer.makeTextLineOnRange(Unknown Source)\r\n        at java.awt.font.TextMeasurer.getLayout(Unknown Source)\r\n...\r\n        at javax.swing.text.JTextComponent.setDocument(Unknown Source)\r\n        at org.apache.jmeter.visualizers.SamplerResultTab.setTextOptimized(SamplerResultTab.java:695)\r\n...\r\n```\r\n"}
{"id":1141114629,"created_at":"2022-02-17T09:56:45Z","updated_at":"2022-03-30T16:06:09Z","state":"closed","title":"JDK-8282046: Create a regression test for JDK-8000326","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/7512","body":"Create a regression test for CCC8000326\r\n\r\nIssue is identified by [JDK-8000326](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8000326), which identifies that after focus moves into JMenuBar, whose focus traversal key is disabled by default, it never moves to other focusable component.\r\n \r\nBy default, pressing the Tab key does not transfer focus from a JMenuBar which is added to a container together with other Swing components, because the focusTraversalKeysEnabled property of JMenuBar is set to false. To resolve this, you should call the JMenuBar.setFocusTraversalKeysEnabled(true) method.\r\n \r\nThe test verifies focus traversal for the above described scenario.\r\nThis review is for migrating tests from a closed test suite to open.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8282046](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8282046): Create a regression test for JDK-8000326\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Alexey Ivanov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#aivanov) (@aivanov-jdk - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7512/head:pull/7512` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7512`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7512` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7512/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 7512`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 7512`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7512.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7512.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1126815438,"created_at":"2022-02-08T05:34:37Z","updated_at":"2022-03-01T03:11:06Z","state":"closed","title":"choose splash image and sizing based on dpi scaled sizes","html_url":"https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/pull/3437","body":"This fixes https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/issues/3436\r\nIt takes into account the DPI when choosing a splash image.\r\nI tried to get MultiResolutionImage to  work to prevent the pixilation of the splash image on scaled displays, but I guess I don't understand it enough. My impression is it is like mipmapping and that swing will choose the best res at render time, but this does not appear to work, at least for Icons. \r\nBut seeing as this issue is preventing people from using 49.6 on scaled displays, I figured this was a good way to get them back in the game.\r\nIn addition this handles missing splash images, which the old code did not do correctly."}

{"id":1138427594,"created_at":"2022-02-15T09:40:16Z","updated_at":"2022-02-24T22:24:45Z","state":"closed","title":"Repaint doesn't work properly on putClientProperty ","html_url":"https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/issues/480","body":"Hi,\r\nI had a case in an app I code on where an action on a button changed whether or not a combobox was valid. I trimmed everything down to a very minimalistic case :\r\n```\r\nimport javax.swing.JButton;\r\nimport javax.swing.JComboBox;\r\nimport javax.swing.JFrame;\r\nimport javax.swing.JPanel;\r\nimport javax.swing.UIManager;\r\nimport javax.swing.UnsupportedLookAndFeelException;\r\n\r\nimport com.formdev.flatlaf.FlatLightLaf;\r\n\r\nclass ComboBoxExample extends JFrame implements ItemListener {\r\n\r\n\tstatic JFrame frame;\r\n\tstatic JComboBox combobox;\r\n\tstatic JButton button;\r\n\r\n\tpublic static void main(String[] args) {\r\n\t\ttry {\r\n\t\t\tUIManager.setLookAndFeel(new FlatLightLaf());\r\n\t\t} catch (UnsupportedLookAndFeelException e) {\r\n\t\t\t//couldn't load flaf\r\n\t\t}\r\n\r\n\t\tframe = new JFrame(\"frame\");\r\n\r\n\t\tComboBoxExample obj = new ComboBoxExample();\r\n\r\n\t\tframe.setLayout(new FlowLayout());\r\n\r\n\t\tString s1[] = { \"yay\", \"nay\" };\r\n\r\n\t\tcombobox = new JComboBox(s1);\r\n\t\tcombobox.setSelectedItem(null);\r\n\t\tcombobox.addItemListener(obj);\r\n\r\n\t\tbutton = new JButton(\"reset\");\r\n\t\tbutton.addActionListener(e -> {\r\n\t\t\tcombobox.setEditable(true);\r\n\t\t\tcombobox.setSelectedItem(null);\r\n\t\t\tcontrolCombo();\r\n\t\t});\r\n\r\n\t\tJPanel p = new JPanel();\r\n\r\n\t\tp.add(combobox);\r\n\t\tp.add(button);\r\n\r\n\t\tframe.add(p);\r\n\t\tframe.setSize(400, 200);\r\n\t\tframe.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);\r\n\t\tframe.setVisible(true);\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\t@Override\r\n\tpublic void itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e) {\r\n\t\tif (e.getSource() == combobox) {\r\n\t\t\tcontrolCombo();\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tprivate static void controlCombo() {\r\n\t\tif (String.valueOf(combobox.getEditor().getItem()).isBlank()) {\r\n\t\t\tcombobox.putClientProperty(\"JComponent.outline\", \"warning\");\r\n\t\t} else {\r\n\t\t\tcombobox.putClientProperty(\"JComponent.outline\", null);\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t}\r\n}\r\n```\r\nIn this example, the combobox is considered at fault when empty, I don't run a check at first.\r\n![InitialState](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55491636/154034575-cd4e435a-21b2-47f7-8116-e899e0af775f.png)\r\nThe steps to reproduce my issue is to click the \"reset\" button right away. Doing so will call the controller of the combobox and find it to be faulty, thus calling ```combobox.putClientProperty(\"JComponent.outline\", \"warning\");```. However, the outline is not painted properly.\r\n![IncompleteOutline](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55491636/154034574-dbdfec7f-340e-435b-bdc0-c980ce71eef6.png)\r\nWhen I hover over the arrow, the outline is completed, but the colour isn't quite the right one. \r\n![WrongColourTooLight](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55491636/154034576-ed7decc2-0fb3-46af-a077-40016dc36128.png)\r\nWhen I get the focus the outline is fixed.\r\n![Expectedoutline](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55491636/154034573-1b71103d-1750-4179-b7c9-977276a002bb.png)\r\nTwo workarounds I found are : forcing the repaint after calling the controller from the button or requesting the focus on the combobox after calling the controller from the button. Forcing the focus changes the expected behaviour so I'm avoiding that method.\r\nCould that be an issue on FlatLaf's side?"}
{"id":1099474141,"created_at":"2022-01-11T18:06:30Z","updated_at":"2022-01-17T13:50:08Z","state":"closed","title":"Update FlatLaf from 1.6.1 to 2.0","html_url":"https://github.com/apache/netbeans/pull/3445","body":"Update FlatLaf to v2: https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/releases/tag/2.0\r\n\r\nThere are (nearly) no visual differences compared to previous used version, except the slightly changed [check boxes and radio buttons](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/pull/414).\r\n\r\nThe main benefits of FlatLaf v2 for NetBeans are the reworked [core themes](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/pull/390) (easier changing colors), the possibility to [change the accent color](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/pull/375) and the [FlatLaf Theme Editor](https://www.formdev.com/flatlaf/theme-editor/). This should it make it relative easy to change colors/style of the light and dark themes to differentiate more from IntelliJ IDEA look.\r\n\r\nE.g. adding following to `platform/o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf/src/org/netbeans/swing/laf/flatlaf/FlatLightLaf.properties`\r\n~~~\r\n@background = #f3f3f3\r\n@accentColor = #007aff\r\n~~~\r\n\r\nwould change the look to (blue accent color; background minimally lighter):\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5604048/148990227-2b6e9ba3-4ae5-4917-8dba-b7eea54ffc69.png)\r\n\r\n\r\nOr adding following to `platform/o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf/src/org/netbeans/swing/laf/flatlaf/FlatDarkLaf.properties`\r\n\r\n~~~\r\n@background = #333\r\n@foreground = #c4c4c4\r\n@accentColor = darken(#007aff,5%)\r\n\r\nButton.default.foreground = #ddd\r\n~~~\r\n\r\nwould make NetBeans darker and give text more contrast:\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5604048/148990745-0c0c2c64-2213-46c8-8bc7-e73cbc3edb5a.png)\r\n\r\nNot sure how to \"organize\" work/ideas on such theme changes...\r\nMaybe create two \"Draft PRs\" (for light and dark) where interested people can comment and add commits?"}

{"id":1201213587,"created_at":"2022-04-12T06:44:41Z","updated_at":"2022-04-27T16:53:38Z","state":"closed","title":"JDK-8284726: Print active locale settings in hs_err reports and in VM.info","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8194","body":"To analyze locale problems in native code - e.g. stemming from third-party code calling `setlocale(3)` - it would be useful to print the active locale settings in hs-err reports and in VM.info.\r\n\r\nPatch notes: \r\n- Posix is fuzzy about the exact role of LC_ALL. It defines LC_ALL as a way to set all locales in one go, but the implementation could still keep the individual categories separately and just let LC_ALL override the individual settings. Therefore I opted to print both, even though on glibc the information seems redundant.\r\n- Since this is Posix specific, callers require #ifndef _WIN32 in shared files. That's not nice, but the alternative would be an empty stub implementation for windows, which I find also unappealing.\r\n\r\nExample output, Ubuntu 20.04:\r\n\r\nJava started with LC_ALL=C:\r\n```\r\nthomas@starfish $ jcmd Simple VM.info | ack LC_\r\nLC_ALL=C\r\nLC_ALL=C\r\nLC_COLLATE=C\r\nLC_CTYPE=C\r\nLC_MESSAGES=C\r\nLC_MONETARY=C\r\nLC_NUMERIC=C\r\nLC_TIME=C\r\n```\r\n\r\nJava started with my default system settings:\r\n```\r\nthomas@starfish $ jcmd Simple VM.info | ack LC_\r\nLC_ALL=LC_CTYPE=C;LC_NUMERIC=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_TIME=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_COLLATE=C;LC_MONETARY=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_MESSAGES=C;LC_PAPER=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_NAME=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_ADDRESS=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_TELEPHONE=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_MEASUREMENT=en_DK.UTF-8;LC_IDENTIFICATION=en_DK.UTF-8\r\nLC_COLLATE=C\r\nLC_CTYPE=C\r\nLC_MESSAGES=C\r\nLC_MONETARY=en_DK.UTF-8\r\nLC_NUMERIC=en_DK.UTF-8\r\nLC_TIME=en_DK.UTF-8\r\n```\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! {"id":1183690006,"created_at":"2022-03-28T16:30:50Z","updated_at":"2022-03-30T17:26:33Z","state":"closed","title":"8283700: Add final or sealed modifier to appropriate java.awt API classes","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/7998","body":"JDK 17 delivered JEP 409: Sealed Classes : https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/409\r\nIn essence this JEP allows a class to limit which classes can subclass it.\r\nIf a class has no subclasses and cannot be subclassed outside the JDK it can also be made final.\r\nSuitable classes across the JDK are being retro-fitted to be sealed (or made final) where it can be done compatibly.\r\nThis fix takes care of several AWT classes which were identified.\r\nIf later we need to remove sealed or make a class non-final that will also be a compatible change,\r\nso we aren't locking ourselves into this.\r\n\r\nAll our automated regression tests - plus JCK tests have been run.\r\n\r\nThis will require a CSR\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n- [x] Change requires a CSR request to be approved\n\n### Issues\n * [JDK-8283700](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8283700): Add final or sealed modifier to appropriate java.awt API classes\n * [JDK-8283813](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8283813): Add final or sealed modifier to appropriate java.awt API classes (**CSR**)\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Joe Darcy](https://openjdk.java.net/census#darcy) (@jddarcy - **Reviewer**)\n * [Alexey Ivanov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#aivanov) (@aivanov-jdk - **Reviewer**)\n * [Sergey Bylokhov](https://openjdk.java.net/census#serb) (@mrserb - **Reviewer**)\n * [Prasanta Sadhukhan](https://openjdk.java.net/census#psadhukhan) (@prsadhuk - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7998/head:pull/7998` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7998`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7998` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7998/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 7998`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 7998`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7998.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7998.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":1127198478,"created_at":"2022-02-08T12:34:07Z","updated_at":"2022-02-08T13:10:31Z","state":"closed","title":"Draw the first frame before window is visible","html_url":"https://github.com/JetBrains/androidx/pull/182","body":"Fixes https://github.com/JetBrains/compose-jb/issues/1794\r\n\r\n[RelNote] The first frame of the window draws before window is visible to avoid flickering\r\n\r\nIf the first frame is too long to draw (> 500ms), you should make their apps asynchronous and draw UI gradually in multiple frames without blocking the UI thread for too long in a single frame. Alternative to that is to use `ComposeWindow` directly (see [the tutorial](https://github.com/JetBrains/compose-jb/tree/master/tutorials/Window_API_new#swing-interoperability)). `ComposeWindow` behave the same way as Swing behaves (draws the first frame only after the window is visible)."}

{"id":936089998,"created_at":"2021-07-02T22:08:37Z","updated_at":"2022-02-23T04:55:13Z","state":"closed","title":"[fixes #697] Added Photo Studio settings saving","html_url":"https://github.com/openrocket/openrocket/pull/975","body":"This PR fixes #697 which was a feature request for saving the Photo Studio settings, not just in one session, but also on the .ork-file.\r\n\r\nCommit 52fa955 adds the basic saving mechanism for PhotoSettings, very similar to how other objects/properties are saved.  Commit 886e300 just moves some files. Finally, I found that there were dependency issues because the core module was trying to use files from the swing module, causing circular dependencies and other nasty stuff. Big thanks to @wolsen for helping me understand and solve this problem. Finally, commit 568abec is the fix for the dependency problem. Basically, the PhotoSettings from the swing module is represented in the core module as a map of Strings that encapsulates the parameters of Photo Studio. Saving and opening the mapped PhotoSettings is done in PhotoStudioSaver and PhotoStudioHandler. The swing module's PhotoStudioGetter and PhotoStudioSetter handle the real PhotoSettings events. They can get and set the mapped PhotoSettings of the core module through theses classes.\r\n\r\nHere is a [jar file](https://www.dropbox.com/s/5b7qgqic1x3ht1d/OpenRocket-697.jar?dl=0) for testing."}

{"id":1204729102,"created_at":"2022-04-14T16:13:59Z","updated_at":"2022-04-19T14:26:10Z","state":"closed","title":"8284539: Configure --with-source-date=version fails on MacOS","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8247","body":"JDK-8282769 added support for more ISO-8601 formats, but remove handling of just a date \"YYYY-MM-DD\" being present, which is the case for a configure using --with-source-date=version which uses the date string from version-numbers.conf.\r\nAlso, the first date parse had an invalid format string \"%FZ %TZ\", with too many Zs.\r\nThis PR corrects the first date parse to parse a standard ISO-8601 Zulu date&time: \"%FT%TZ\"\r\nThen it adds the final check for no time being specified.\r\n\r\nSigned-off-by: Andrew Leonard <anleonar@redhat.com>\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [x] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8284539](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8284539): Configure --with-source-date=version fails on MacOS\n\n\n### Reviewers\n * [Erik Joelsson](https://openjdk.java.net/census#erikj) (@erikj79 - **Reviewer**)\n * [Magnus Ihse Bursie](https://openjdk.java.net/census#ihse) (@magicus - **Reviewer**)\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8247/head:pull/8247` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8247`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8247` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8247/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8247`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8247`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8247.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8247.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

This\nwould allow a malicious class to be instantiated that could execute arbitrary code from the JVM. Fixed in <a href=\"https://github.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/commit/f4d0ed69c0b3aae8531d83d6af4c57f22312c813\">commit<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3>Changed<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li>perf: read in_hot_standby GUC on SQLException instead of ClassCastException when calling\nCallableStatement#getBoolean(int) on BIT(&gt;1).<\/li>\n<li>style: import java.time types in more classes [PR <a for java.time types in all remaining classes.<\/li>\n<li>style: import java.time types in TimestampUtils [PR <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2380\">#2380<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2380\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2380<\/a>) Use imports for java.time types in TimestampUtils.<\/li>\n<li>refactor: Change internal constructors to pass only connection Properties\nChanges internal constructors for PgConnection and related classes to only accept the connection properties object and\nremove the user and password arguments. Any locations that required those fields can retrieve them from the properties map.<\/li>\n<li>test: Fix DatabaseMetadataTest to perform mview tests only on 9.3+<\/li>\n<li>perf: read in_hot_standby GUC on connection [PR <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2334\">#2334<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2334\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2334<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>doc: improv doc around binary decoding of numeric data <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2331\">#2331<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Add cert key type checking to chooseClientAlias [PR <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2417\">#2417<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2417\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2417<\/a>)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3>Added<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li>feat: Add authenticationPluginClassName option to provide passwords at runtime\nAdds authenticationPluginClassName connection property that allows end users to specify a class\nthat will provide the connection passwords at runtime. Users implementing that interface must\nensure that each invocation of the method provides a new char[] array as the contents\nwill be filled with zeroes by the driver after use.Call sites within the driver have been updated to use the char[] directly wherever possible.\nThis includes direct usage in the GSS authentication code paths that internally were already converting the String password into a char[] for internal usage.\nThis allows configuring a connection with a password that must be generated on the fly or periodically changes. [PR <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2369\">#2369<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2369\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2369<\/a>) original issue [Issue <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2102\">#2102<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2102\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2102<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>feat: add tcpNoDelay option [PR <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2341\">#2341<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/pull/2341\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2341<\/a>) fixes [Issue <a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2324\">#2324<\/a>](<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/issues/2324\">pgjdbc/pgjdbc#2324<\/a>)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<!-- raw HTML omitted -->\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>...
